<HEAD>President's Son Denies Ties to Party Member Accused of Corruption</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with quotes
from politician involved and party leader. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON> on Monday ridiculed reports he was involved in misusing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid money. `` Can you imagine that if I had ... -LRB- $ 2 million -RRB- I would still be in this country?,'' he asked. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s son denied he was trying to protect <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON>, a fellow <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> who was reported under investigation in the case. `` I deny any tie because I am not protecting him and because I am against corruption,'' said <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, candidate for mayor of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in the March 20 elections. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday that <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> is being investigated for allegedly misusing up to $ 2 million of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. It said the money was part of a $ 10 million program to assist war-ravaged areas and help win the support of Salvadorans in the war against leftist rebels. The newspaper quoted unidentified Salvadoran and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials as saying it could be the largest case of theft of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid money during the administration of President <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, elected in May 1984 for a five-year term. In an interview with local newspapers, <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> said `` that news -LRB- about alleged misuse of funds -RRB- surprises me because it is totally false.'' <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Claramount </PERSON>, <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s vice president and secretary-general of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the article was `` full of vagueness and imprecisions with the political intention of damaging the party.'' He said it was written `` within a strategic conception of the ultra-right of the country.'' He also read a communique saying the party backed <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> as `` an absolutely honorable, capable and honest man.'' Referring to allegations against <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON>, the communique said `` we abstain from making a value judgment because we do not know if there is evidence.'' <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> denied being an associate of <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> and said he had urged <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> to cooperate with any investigation. `` It is vital that the truth be arrived at,'' he told reporters. `` If he -LRB- <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> -RRB- is clean, he does not have to be afraid. If he feels he is outside of the accusations, then he should submit himself to any investigation.'' `` All this is a dirty political game and I feel indignant for having been involved,'' <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> said. Asked about his relationship with <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON>, he replied, `` I have no personal friendship with him. I know him like the majority of the members of the party.'' The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> resigned three months ago as director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restoration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Areas </ORGANIZATION>, but President <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> agreed to allow him to become a party candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZ