<HEAD>Rockwell Pleads Innocent in Overbilling Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and two former managers pleaded innocent Monday to charges that they overbilled the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> by $ 450,000 on a sophisticated satellite navigational system. In a brief hearing, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Consuelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> ordered the company and its former managers to file pretrial motions by April 4 and set a May 3 trial date, <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Charney </PERSON> said. He indicated the company plans to make pretrial motions but declined to elaborate. The company and the former managers _ <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, materials division director at the its Seal Beach plant, and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavodnick </PERSON>, manager of major subcontracts within the division _ were named in a 25-count federal indictment in January. The indictment alleged that the company and two men double-billed the government for work on the NAVSTAR global navigational system that uses radio signals from satellites to pinpoint locations on earth. As a result, the indictment claimed, <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> received $ 450,000 in unlawful profits. The company has denied the allegations.
