<SECOND>PM-China-Soviet-Minorities,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Communist Powers Face Similar Minority Problems
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Militant monks in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and restive Armenians in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are among the minority nationalities in those countries now testing, sometimes with violence, the limits of their governments' professed policies of openness. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> calls them `` hooligans.'' To <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> they are `` splittists.'' But to both countries they represent a threat to the reputation and unity of the state. Thirty-one people died last week in rioting in the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, where Christian Armenians are unhappy about being part of mostly Moslem <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, up to 23 have died in clashes between <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> police and Tibetans in October and over the weekend. In both countries, the Communist governments in the past have suppressed their minorities to unite vast tracts of land under the ruling ethnic group, the <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the Russians in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> purged the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> in the 1930s, and <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> swiftly cracked down on unrest in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and Moslem west <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the 1950s and 1960s. Both countries, with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the lead, have now declared greater tolerance for different views, exposing both to flashpoints of nationalist sentiment. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> blames outside forces for its troubles, saying pro-independence supporters of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s exiled religious leader, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, were responsible for the first outbreak of violence in the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> last October. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> is faced with a wider problem of ethnic disputes in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, religious identity in <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION> and political activism in the Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. Foreign journalists in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have had slightly better access to the troubled areas than their Moscow-based counterparts. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> expelled 14 foreign journalists from <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> last October, and has since given permission for only a few to return. But <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> authorities, hungry for tourist spending to help <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s poorest province, have not stopped group tours, and some reporters have joined excursion groups to <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> let a few correspondents go to <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, on a Foreign Ministry-sponsored trip for a planned demonstration to mark the Feb. 16 declaration of independence. But reporters there were followed constantly. No foreign journalist has been allowed lately into <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Telephone calls to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> sometimes went through, but <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, the center of the Armenian-Azeri dispute, can not be reached at all and <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> only rarely. Reflecting <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s `` glasnost'' and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s similar policy of `` kaifang,'' the official media in both countries have carried limited reports of the disturbances. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s press has stressed that only a small number of Tibetans have joined the disturbances, and has sent out a barrage of stories about Tibetans criticizing the separatists and saying how much better life is under socialism. The government has stressed that it will continue to respect the local customs and help alleviate poverty in the regions where the nation's 67 million non-Han minorities live. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, too, has linked the rioting to a small number of `` hooligans.'' Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, however, in a Feb. 18 speech stressed the importance of working out a new policy on nationalities and said the <ORGANIZATION> Cental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> would hold a special plenary session to discuss the matter.
</TEXT>
