<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Near Collision,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Pilot Sentenced For False Statements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Army private who flew his small airplane into prohibited airspace over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> ranch must spend 30 weekends in jail. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, 33, of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, convicted of lying to authorities about the reason he strayed into prohibited airspace on Aug. 13, was sentenced Monday by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Real </PERSON>. Despite a Probation Department recommendation of probation, Real sentenced <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> to three years in jail for each of two counts of making false statements and then suspended all but 60 days of the incarceration. The judge also ordered <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> to donate 1,000 hours to charitable service. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>' jail time will begin April 9 and is not to interfere with his military service. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> could have been sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment and a $ 500,000 fine Outside court, <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said he was made a scapegoat by the federal government because reports that there had been a near-miss caused `` hysteria.'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> maintains his plane was no closer than 800 feet from the president's helicopter, Marine One. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> pilot, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON>, says <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>' plane passed about 200 feet in front of his helicopter and 150 feet below it. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Araujo </PERSON>, said they will appeal the sentence. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, who has been stripped of his pilot's license, originally told federal agents he strayed into the prohibited airspace while looking for a lost contact lens in the cabin. He later said he had lied about the lens because, `` I was trying to stay out of more trouble.'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> was demoted from private first class to private for being absent without leave. He still has 18 months left in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>.
