<HEAD>Men Backing New Panama Government Smash Into Consulate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Delvalle ousted Feb. 26, sted last week, in grafs 3,
10.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of men backing <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s new government seized control of the country's disputed consulate in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Monday night by smashing through the glass door with a Land Rover, police reported. The <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said the seizure took place because the consul in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arango </PERSON>, refused to give up his post despite being fired by the new government. Control of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is also in dispute following the ouster on Feb. 26 of President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. He was removed from office after he tried to dismiss Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the military leader and de facto ruler. The <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> consulate is about a mile east of the embassy. The <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Arango </PERSON> was not in the consulate when the raid occurred. Police said in a statement that six men _ two representatives of Panamanian Ambassador <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> and four members of a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> security firm _ smashed their way into the consulate. `` Shortly after this, several people left the building, including three women believed to be secretaries, and a number of security staff. One glass-paneled front door was damaged and no one was injured as a result of the incident,'' the statement added. One of the staff members forced out of the consulate, Tourism Commissioner <PERSON> Rolando </PERSON> <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON>, 24, said: `` We were just working in there and then suddenly we heard a crash.'' He said the Land Rover broke through the glass doors and then a group of men burst into the building carrying large hammers. `` They threatened us with hammers and one tried to hit my face. They took my passport and documents. Then they pushed me down the stairs and out of the building,'' <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> police sealed off the area around the consulate in <LOCATION> Tudor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> in the City, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s financial district. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and many other countries still consider <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> the president of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. He was removed from office by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, which is dominated by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> supporters. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has called for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s ouster since he was indicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> last month on drug trafficking charges. The <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> reported that <PERSON> Arango </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> at the time of <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s ouster and has said he helped smuggle <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> from his residence to a hiding place in the Central American country. The British domestic news agency <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Arango </PERSON> received a phone call at home from the consulate staff about the Monday night raid. The agency quoted <PERSON> Arango </PERSON> as saying he was prevented from entering the consulate after the attack and that one of the men occupying it had told him they were working for <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> and carrying out orders from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. British government officials said they were told last Friday that <PERSON> Arango </PERSON> was being fired as consul. <PERSON> Arango </PERSON> said he had received letters from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> saying he was dismissed but had ignored them, <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said. As workmen repaired the doors, one of the British security guards who took part in the raid said: `` It is an exaggeration to say we smashed in. We nudged the doors with the Land Rover. The police say they may prosecute us for mounting the pavement -LRB- sidewalk -RRB- but I do n't think they can do anything else. We were authorized to enter the building but I can not divulge any more.'' The four guards involved work for GB Security, a private security company based in south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. They said they would be guarding the building overnight. A spokesman at the British <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, who in accordance with British practice declined to be named, said it was too early to say what action, if any, Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> might take over the incident.
