<HEAD>Chairman of St. Joseph News-Press &amp; Gazette Co. Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOSEPH, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has died at age 70. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, who died Sunday at a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hospital, was the second generation of a communications family that has published The <ORGANIZATION> News-Press </ORGANIZATION> and Gazette for nearly 50 years. He was publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> newspapers </ORGANIZATION> from 1956 to 1981, succeeding his father, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, as president of the company in 1972. The elder <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> died in 1973. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> was known for keeping the newspapers on the leading edge of technology, switching to all-electronic production more than a decade ago. He also led the company into the TV market. The company's holdings include stations in <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, Miss.; <LOCATION> Hattiesburg </LOCATION>, Miss.; <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and cable TV systems in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. He was active in The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and served as a director of the news cooperative from 1970 to 1979. He also was first vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>, servi