<HEAD>Demands For Religious Freedom After Packed Mass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Roman Catholics chanted `` We want religious freedom!'' after thousands crowded into a cathedral for a Mass honoring a 13th-century Czech princess who renounced royal wealth to serve God. The Mass on Sunday at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vitus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION>, in the Castle complex where Communist President <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON> lives, drew about 8,000 people. It was one of the biggest religious services in the capital since the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> takeover in 1948 and an indication of the reviving strength of the nation's Roman Catholic church. Dozens of plainclothes security officers were seen inside and outside the cathedral while Mass was held to honor the princess who is to be canonized by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> later this year. Police arrested 16 dissidents and religious activists under 48-hour detention orders on Friday and Saturday, apparently to prevent them from attending the Mass. A dissident source said five people remained in detention Sunday night, but four of them were expected to be freed today. <PERSON> Augustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navratil </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic activist from <LOCATION> Moravia </LOCATION>, was detained Friday morning but there was no word he was free late Sunday, the source said. <PERSON> Navratil </PERSON> was the author of a 31-point church petition for more religious freedom that has gained more than 300,000 signatures, making it the largest such action in the Soviet bloc since 1945. Five other dissidents were briefly detained when they tried to visit a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> diplomat Friday, and two others also were briefly held that night. After the Mass, about 1,000 people went from the cathedral to the nearby residence of Cardinal <PERSON> Frantisek </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON>. A few hundred chanted `` We want bishops,'' `` We want religious freedom'' and `` We want the Pope.'' The chanting crowd appeared to reflect growing discontent among Catholics at the lack of bishops in 10 of the country's 13 sees. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> has refused to accept government proposals to appoint as bishops members of the state-sponsored Pacem in <LOCATION> Terris </LOCATION> organization, a group of priests not recognized by the Holy See. `` Long live the Holy Father'' was another chant from the crowd outside <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON>'s residence, which adjoins the castle where <PERSON> Husak </PERSON> lives. The presidential flag was flying, indicating the 75-year-old president was home during the unusual demonstration. There is no official estimate of the number of believers in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials estimate about 60 percent of the 15.5 million citizens are <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>.
