<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Democratic Forum,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unofficial Democratic Forum Discusses Romanian Minority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hungarian intellectuals and a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> have called on <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to allow more ethnic Hungarian refugees to emigrate from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and appealed for international support in monitoring their rights. About 20 people spoke at the all-day forum Sunday in a theater in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. More than 700 people attended the meeting, participants informed The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by telephone from the Hungarian capital. The meeting Sunday was the second one of the `` Democratic Forum'' since the group was formed on Sept. 27 in southern <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. The document issued at the September meeting called for `` genuinely effective reform'' to resolve <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s economic and social problems. The meetings are unusual in communist <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> because authorities, although they have not officially recognized the forum, have not prevented them from taking place, and the results have been discussed in the official press. Most of the speakers Sunday focused on the ethnic Hungarian minority in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> are <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact allies but have engaged in increasingly sharp rhetoric over the question of the ethnic Hungarian minority in <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> in recent months. <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> was ruled by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> before World War I, and both nations claim the area is the cradle of their national cultures and history. Hungarian officials say increasing numbers of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s nearly 2 million ethnic Hungarians have sought refuge in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Geza </PERSON> <PERSON> Szoecs </PERSON>, an ethnic Hungarian poet from <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> who now lives in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, suggested that the Hungarian government consider allowing a certain quota of ethnic Hungarians from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> emigrate to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. He suggested the quota correlate to the number of Hungarians who apply for asylum in the West each year, as well as the general decline of the population through the sinking birthrate. However, <PERSON> Zoltan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiraly </PERSON>, a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, warned against establishing a refugee program that would help Romanian Communist leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> get rid of the Hungarian minority. Ethnic Hungarians have said they are increasingly restricted in the use of their language and expression of their culture in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, which denies the charges and accuses <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> of meddling in its affairs. <PERSON> Kiraly </PERSON> told the gathering he and five other parliamentarians drafted a resolution calling on the government to set up a settlement fund for Transylvanian Hungarians who wish to stay in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. He said the draft resolution, which is to be put before <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> when it meets in spring session later this month, also calls on the government to seek the cooperation of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and to mobilize international public opinion. <PERSON> Kiraly </PERSON>, one of the most outspoken members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, said many Hungarians who enter <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> go on to third countries because the Hungarian authorities are not prepared to receive them. He said many of these ethnic Hungarians, if given the chance, would opt to stay in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> because of the cultural affinity.
