<SECOND>PM-Ferry Memorial,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tears, Pleas For A New Beginning On Ferry Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZEEBRUGGE, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Survivors and those who lost loved ones in a ferry disaster retraced the voyage of the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>, casting wreaths and notes over the spot where it capsized a year before. `` Daddy, Miss You,'' said one of the more than 100 cards dropped into the water Sunday, a cold, bleak day with a fine drizzle _ remarkably similar to the day the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> turned over and 193 of its passengers died. Others joined in prayer Sunday in this Belgian port and across the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> in the English port of <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> to mark the worst peacetime disaster involving a British ship since the sinking of the Titanic in 1912. About 270 set out from <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION> and stopped just outside the harbor wall where the ferry capsized March 6, 1987, when water rushed in through its open bow doors five minutes after it left port. For 20 minutes they cast flowers onto the choppy seas from the Baltic Ferry, which the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>'s owners P and O pressed into service for the sad pilgrimage. Some were led away to be comforted by <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and social workers. Others clung to their families. A few went off by themselves and stood looking into the murky waters. On the upper car deck, which was transformed into a makeshift chapel bedecked with flowers, prayers were said by three clergymen _ an Anglican, a <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> and a major from the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> _ during a half-hour service. `` This service can mark a new beginning,'' said The Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowers </PERSON>, vicar of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s and <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>. `` It does not mean we forget those who we have loved. ... In fact, it is from that memory that we build a new future.'' His words were echoed by The Bishop of <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>, The Rt. Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Third </PERSON>, who told more than 600 bereaved at the Anglican church of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> that it was time to leave their grief behind. `` It is right to grieve. It is health-giving to express your sorrow _ but you ca n't go on doing it for a lifetime. There must come a moment when you surrender your grief, when you stop crying.'' At St. Donaas Roman Catholic church across the road from <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION> port, the Sunday service was turned into a memorial for the ferry victims. The Rev. <PERSON> Wim </PERSON> <PERSON> Catry </PERSON> also offered prayers that the survivors and bereaved would be able to reconstruct their lives. He said in his sermon that a rose garden and plaque would be unveiled in May in front of the church to commemorate the dead. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who turned his body into a human bridge so 20 passengers including his wife and daughter could walk across his back to safety, paid his own private tribute. He went out on a Belgian tug to the spot where the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> capsized and with his 13-year-old daughter <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> dropped 193 flowers into the water, one by one. His wife, <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON>, like several other Britons who came here, remained onshore, unable at the last minute to relive their nightmares. Said Mrs. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>: `` I hate this day _ I just wish I could take it off the calendar.''
</TEXT>
