<HEAD>Talks Resume With Pakistan Insisting On Interim Afghan Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CLARIFIES lead. INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `Soviet
leader ...,' to UPDATE with Zia interview. PICKS up 5th graf, `Upon
his ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 U.N.-sponsored <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> peace talks resumed today with uncertainty persisting over whether <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is ready to sign an agreement with the Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government which it does not recognize. Resumption of talks came after unprecedented consultations between the Pakistani government and opposition leaders attended by <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>'s chief negotiator, acting Foreign Minister <PERSON> Zain </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON>. Sources close to the meetings held during the weekend in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> said most of 19 opposition parties urged the government not to stand in the way of the proposed pullout of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops helping <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to fight Moslem insurgents. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said a withdrawal could start in mid-May if a settlement is signed by next week. In an interview published today, Pakistani President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> said his country will not budge from its demand for an interim government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> as part of a settlement. The Gulf News daily reported that <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> was optimistic that the proposed peace accord on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will be signed on schedule. `` There is no question of the accord not going through. Allowing it to be dropped is no option,'' he was quoted as saying. Upon his return to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Sunday night, <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said the formation of a broad-based transitional government was as important as the troop withdrawl in bringing peace to the region. `` Why should we not insist on an interim government,'' he said in response to a question from a reporter at the airport. Last week <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> would make up its mind after the <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> consultations on whether to sign a settlement with the present <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, which <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> does not recognize. He put up only a cryptic smile when asked again before today's session if <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> was now prepared to sign <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has insisted that any agreement on the withdrawal Soviet troops should be linked to formation of an interim government that is acceptable to all sides in the 9-year-old war. The <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> government says this is the only way to ensure the safe repatriation of 5 million Afghan refugees from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has been representing Afghan rebels at the U.N.-sponsored talks, which began in 1982. The resistance movements, which say they represent 200,000 guerrillas, have rejected any power-sharing with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and have presented a plan of their own for an Islamic government The Afghan government says its own policy of national reconciliation envisages a `` coalition government'' open to all political forces including the Pakistan-based resistance movements. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which sent its troops in December 1979 to help a faltering Marxist government suppress a Moslem insurrection, no longer demands a transitional government be formed before withdrawal. <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> undersecretary general who has been mediating the Afghan talks, said last week all major differences had been resolved in the first three days of the new negotiating round, which began last Wednesday. The two sides agreed on a nine-month timetable for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said this agreement, following years of stalling on the timetable issue, represented a `` significant step'' toward a final political settlement. The sides also agreed that half of the Soviet troops would leave in the first three-month phase, the so-called `` front-end loading'' which had been a major concern of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
