<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> shot missiles into each other's capitals today and both reported dozens of deaths as the `` war of the cities'' persisted between the two <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war foes. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said 12 civilians, including women and children, were killed and 30 wounded when an Iraqi missile exploded in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> today. It said a hospital clinic, several houses and 30 vehicles were destroyed in the blast. The missile was one of three <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said its army shot into <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> early today in the latest round of the bruising offensive that has claimed hundreds of lives in both countries. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> said another 61 civilians were killed and 427 wounded Sunday in Iraqi air raids on 16 Iranian cities and towns. The agency said schools and hospitals were hit in the wave of Iraqi raids on the southern city of <LOCATION> Shiraz </LOCATION> and Dezful, <LOCATION> Arak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Khorramabad </LOCATION> and other population centers in the west. Eight other people were wounded in missile strikes on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> on Sunday, it said. It said Iraqi artillery was shelling the northwestern border town of <LOCATION> Marivan </LOCATION>, but made no mention of casualties or damage. <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> communiques said <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> fighter-bombers flew 118 combat missions against `` military and economic targets'' in 12 Iranian cities Sunday in retaliation for `` criminal attacks on Iraqi civilian areas.'' <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> reported that Revolutionary Guards fired four missiles into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> today. It said they were aimed at `` military centers.'' <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> said the first two missiles crashed into residential sections of the capital, killing or wounding `` many civilians, including women and children.'' The agency said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> retaliated by firing three long-range `` <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'' missiles, named after a 7th Century Shiite Moslem saint, into <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> today. <ORGANIZATION> INA </ORGANIZATION> quoted a military communique as saying: `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s rulers must realize their weakness and stop fighting.'' The eight-day missile exchange has been the fiercest since the gulf war began in September 1980 and the first time that <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> has been hit by missiles. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> says it has fired 41 projectiles into the Iranian capital since the eye-for-an-eye missile duel began Feb. 29, when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> sent two missiles crashing into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Foreign Minister, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON>, admitted Saturday that `` more than 30'' missiles had hit <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. The Iranians have reported firing 22 missiles in that period, but the Iraqis have only acknowledged 18 hits. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has reported at least 106 civilians killed and more than 200 wounded in the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missile blitz, with more than 100 killed and more than 500 wounded in air raids over the last week. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has reported heavy civilian casualties, but has given no numbers.
