<HEAD>Teen-ager Upset About School, Basketball Shoots Up Own House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIGA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 15-year-old boy described as despondent over school problems and upset about the outcome of a college basketball game blasted away with an assortment of rifles and handguns for five hours inside his home, officials said today. No one was injured in the incident, which ended when deputies talked the boy into surrendering early today, said <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's spokesman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. `` The house is a shambles,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said this morning. `` He shot out the television, the stove, the walls and ceilings, windows, sliding glass doors, a water pipe which ruptured and squirted water everywhere, and even the electrical box in the basement.'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said the boy, whose name was withheld because of his age, had picked up a gun and started shooting Sunday night. His mother ran next door to call police. When deputies arrived at the house in the rural area southwest of <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, they heard bullets whizzing by their heads and evacuated the house next door. Deputies then set up a command post in a house down the road, from which negotiators talked to the youth by telephone, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. Before the boy surrendered early Sunday morning he had fired at least 300 rounds of ammunition had been fired from a variety of weapons, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. The boy's father had four or five rifles and shotguns and four handguns, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` The boy had been suspended from high school last week for disciplinary problems,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` Whether this triggered him, we do n't know. The only other thing he mentioned to hostage negotiators was that he was upset that <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> lost to <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> edged <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> 85-84 to take the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> college basketball title Sunday afternoon. The youth was taken to Strong Memorial Hospital in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> for a mental examination before being turned over to family court officials, said <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>.
