<HEAD>Court Will Try Again to Decide on Suing Cities in Ohio Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said today it will try again to decide whether cities may be sued successfully when citizens' rights are violated due to alleged inadequate training of municipal employees The justices said they will study the issue in an appeal by <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, officials. The city is seeking to kill a lawsuit by a woman who says police violated her rights by failing to provide her medical attention after she was arrested for speeding. The justices last year backed out of deciding the municipal-liability issue in a case from <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. By a 5-4 vote, the court declined for procedural reasons to decide whether <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> should be forced to pay damages in the death of a fleeing motorist killed by a policeman's bullet. The ruling left intact a $ 50,000 damage award the city was ordered to pay to the victim's family. The case acted on today involves <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, who was granted a retrial of her lawsuit by a lower court. <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> officials said alleged inadequate training of police in summoning medical help should not be the basis for a lawsuit against the city. Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' lawsuit grows out of an April 26, 1978, incident in which she was stopped for speeding while driving her teen-age daughter to school. Police said they put Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> into a patrol wagon after the 52-year-old woman became upset and uncooperative. On arrival at the police station, the officers said she was lying on the floor of the vehicle. She repeatedly slumped to the floor during a stay of 30 to 40 minutes at the stationhouse. Police officers did not call for medical help. They said they believed Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> was merely excited and would calm down if left alone and permitted to see her family. When family members arrived, they had Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> taken by ambulance to a hospital where she was diagnosed as suffering from stress reaction, anxiety and depression. The symptoms included immobility and difficulty in breathing. She was under psychiatric care for more than a year later. The <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> family sued the city in federal court, and a jury awarded $ 200,000 against the city on grounds Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> unreasonably was denied medical attention. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> threw out the verdict last July, saying it was unclear on what theory the damage award was based. The judge's instructions to the jury could have allowed it to decide erroneously that the city was at fault even if the failure to summon medical attention was not the result of a city policy, the appeals court said. `` This instruction allows a finding of municipal liability merely because -LRB- the city's -RRB- supervisory personnel did a bad act, with no need to find that the city was a bad actor through a city policy or custom. This was error,'' the appeals court said. <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> officials asked the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to throw out the lawsuit. City officials said the 6th Circuit court ruling will allow the city to be found liable for misconduct at the retrial under an unreasonably broad theory. The city may be forced to pay damages if the jury decides that police were not trained adequately to summon medical help in such cases, city officials said. The appeals court ruling will impose `` the novel requirement upon cities that their police forces must provide paramedical officers or other trained medical specialists who exercise some type of professional judgment at the jail,'' city officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> recently has had trouble providing clear guidelines on the issue of inadequate police training as grounds for municipal liability in federal civil rights suits. In a 7-1 ruling in 1985 the justices threw out a $ 1.5 million award against <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in the shooting death of a tavern patron by a police officer. Only four justices agreed it was a mistake for the jury to be told it could infer from a single incident that the city was grossly negligent in its police training. Three other justices voted to throw out the award for other reasons. The case is <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, 86-1088.
