<HEAD>Air Ambulance Firm Accused Of Federal Rule Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> company that provides helicopters and crews for a third of the nation's civilian air ambulance services has been accused of violating federal aviation regulations, probably unintentionally, a newspaper reports. Most of <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s alleged violations involved paperwork and record-keeping deficiencies, The <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> findings stem from a two-month investigation of the company's safety procedures and regulation compliance, said <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Barlow </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>, which covers <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Provo </LOCATION>, The alleged violations are being reviewed and the final number could be fewer than the 120 now pending, <PERSON> Barlow </PERSON> said. `` It looks like a case where a small company based in one location grew very rapidly to the point where it had aircraft and people operating in dozens of states and no real handle on how to manage them,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Rocky Mountain Helicopter, the industry's largest vendor, supplies aircraft, pilots and mechanics to hospitals in 39 cities, including <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Barlow </PERSON> said Rocky Mountain Helicopters faces possible fines because the investigation uncovered a number of significant problems. However, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> believes <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> is now operating in compliance with regulations and the agency had no plans to lift their license to fly. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> <PERSON> Spray </PERSON>, the company's vice president of emergency medical services operations, said, `` We do n't deny we made some mistakes, but we're fixing them as fast as they're being pointed out.'' The inspection was spawned by congressional pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> last year after a record medical helicopter accident rate in 1986, but the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said it also wanted to become more acquainted with the medical helicopter industry. There are more than 235 medical helicopter programs operating at least 500 helicopters in 46 states. `` What we learn from <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> will help us to manage the whole industry better,'' <PERSON> Barlow </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s 143-page report referred to such shortcomings as a lack of documented training in evacuating patients from the aircraft in emergencies, The Press reported. Other alleged violations ranged from a lack of training for the company's pilots to the failure of the director of operations and chief pilot to have the proper <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> licenses for those positions, the newspaper said. On Feb. 12, Rocky Mountain voluntarily grounded 62 of its helicopters until mechanics in each city could confirm all maintenance and accompanying paperwork were up-to-date and accurate. `` In most cases, this -LRB- grounding -RRB- just took long enough for a phone call to each city, but three aircraft were grounded for a day or so for repairs,'' Spray said. On Feb. 17, <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> grounded 24 of its pilots because they did not have the proper paperwork to show they had received required training. `` Within two days, all the pilots were flying legal again,'' Spray said.
