<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Adams, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,450</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, Adams, who, to restore first name</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to consider reinstating the death sentence of a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> man convicted of killing an 8-year-old girl in 1978. The court is expected to use the case to study death row inmates' right to raise new issues when they turn to the federal courts for help and to decide whether <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> juries may be told their life-or-death recommendations are subject to the trial judge's approval. <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, who once worked as a corrections officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Marion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ocala </LOCATION>, was convicted of the Jan. 23, 1978, strangulation of <PERSON> Trisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornley </PERSON> near <LOCATION> Ocala </LOCATION>. His conviction and death sentence have been upheld three times by the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The nation's highest court refused to review his case twice. In the second federal court appeal, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> in early 1986 challenged statements made to the jury by the judge in his state court sentencing trial. Under <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law, a jury recommends life or death for convicted murderers in capital cases. The presiding judge is free to follow or disregard the recommendation. In <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' case, the judge told jurors about that aspect of the state's capital-sentencing law. `` The final decision as to what punishment shall be imposed rests solely upon the judge of this court,'' the jury was told. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> argued that such jury instructions run afoul of a 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in which the justices, ruling in a <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> case, said a death sentence is invalid if a jury is misled about its role in determining whether the defendant actually will die. In the case, a <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> prosecutor had told jurors they should not view themselves as determining life or death because their sentence would be reviewed automatically by an appeals court. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said such a statement misled the jury, and rendered the subsequent death sentence `` cruel and unusual punishment.'' A federal judge dismissed <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' 1986 appeal but the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last Nov. 13 threw out his sentence. The appeals court said the judge's instructions to jurors violated the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 1985 decision, adding that <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> was entitled to `` a new sentencing proceeding before an untainted jury.'' In the appeal acted on today, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> prosecutors noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> previously had rejected an appeal in which <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> mounted an identical challenge to the judge's instructions to jurors. They asked the justices to resolve the conflict between the state's highest court and the 11th Circuit court. The state's appeal also contended that <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' challenge should not have been allowed because he did not raise it in his first federal court appeal. The case is <PERSON> Dugger </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, 87-121.
