<HEAD>Court Refuses to Free Churches from Financial-Disclosure Laws in
Tennessee Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to free churches from having to comply with state financial-disclosure laws when waging public referendum campaigns. The court, citing the lack of a `` substantial federal question,'' turned away a challenge by 13 churches from <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, to a law they contend violates their freedom of religion and freedom of speech. The <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> law also affects other non-political organizations that decided to campaign for or against issues that appear on election ballots. The controversy arose during an August 1984 election held in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> to determine whether establishments within the city would be allowed to sell liquor by the drink. The local option referendum was defeated by a vote of 6,514 to 6,474 _ a 40-vote margin. The 13 area churches, nine of them Baptist-affiliated, took varying steps to make public their opposition to allowing on-premise liquor consumption in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>. The churches spent a total of $ 5,150, mostly for advertising, in opposition to the referendum. But they failed to register as `` political campaign committees'' as required by the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Campaign Financial Disclosure Act of 1980. The law defines such committees as any combination of two or more people `` making expenditures to support or oppose any candidate for public office or measure.'' It requires that the committees designate a political treasurer and file campaign-disclosure statements. The churches sued the state to challenge the law as applied to them. At trial, pastors for the churches testified that the referendum opposition resulted from moral, not political, concerns and that they considered their actions to be part of the churches' religious mission. The pastors also testified that their churches had not, and would not, get involved in partisan political campaigns as a matter of religious conviction. A state trial judge ruled against the churches, finding that all of them are `` political campaign committees'' as defined by the 1980 state law and that the law is constitutional. A state appeals court later overturned the state law as a violation of constitutional free-speech rights. The <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last May 26 ruled that the law does not violate free-speech rights when applied to either partisan elections featuring candidates or non-partisan referendum elections. `` The recent history of campaign financial abuses as well as the growth and possible dominance of special interest political action committees make the state's disclosure requirements necessary to allow the public to have some gauge by which to assess the sources, content and frequency of campaign publicity and activity,'' the state court ruled. Its ruling did not discuss the churches' argument that the law violates their right to exercise freely their religious beliefs. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the 13 churches noted that the justices have `` never passed on the validity of disclosure requirements in referendum campaigns.'' The appeal questioned whether any state may justify `` prior registration and disclosure requirements to non-political organizations in general and churches in particular.'' Tennessee Attorney General W.J. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cody </PERSON> urged the high court to reject the churches' appeal. `` The fact that this is a referendum election does not make the state's interest in providing any information to the voters as to how the election is financed any less compelling,'' <PERSON> Cody </PERSON> said. The 13 churches who challenged the law are <ORGANIZATION> Bemis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pentecostal </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Calvary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Englewood </LOCATION> Baptist, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> God </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bemis </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION>, Malesus Baptist, <PERSON> North </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Baptist </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Northside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> God </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Poplar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Skyline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baptist </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Woodland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baptist </LOCATION>. The case is <PERSON> Bemis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pentecostal </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, 87-317.
