<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling on Criminal Trials in Louisiana Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that the public has no right to attend hearings into the alleged tainting or bribing of a criminal trial jury while the trial is underway. The justices, without comment, refused to second-guess the validity of conducting such hearings in secret during the 1986 racketeering trial of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. A federal appeals court, in upholding the closed hearings, ruled that the public's constitutional right to attend criminal trials does not extend to `` the midtrial questioning of jurors.'' The appeals court also ruled that transcripts of the closed hearings may be withheld from public disclosure during the trial even if the jury is sequestered, and that the names of the jurors involved may be erased from the transcripts. After a 1985 trial ended in mistrial because a federal jury could not reach a unanimous verdict, then-Gov. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and four co-defendants stood trial again in 1986 on charges of racketeering and bribery. All were acquitted after a two-month trial. On two occasions during the second trial, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Livaudais </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> received reports that the sequestered jury had been tainted. The first report suggested that one juror had told another that jury members in <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' first trial were paid to vote for acquittal. The second report suggested one juror had told another of a possible bribery attempt by one defendant. In both instances, <PERSON> Livaudais </PERSON> conducted proceedings in his chambers and determined that the people involved could continue serving as jurors. Courtroom spectators, including news reporters, were given only vague accounts of why the hearings were held. The judge said he would release partial transcripts sometime after the trial was completed, but that those transcripts would not include juror names. Three news organizations _ The <ORGANIZATION> Times-Picayune </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> _ and several of their reporters challenged the judge's use of closed hearings. The Times-Picayune is a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> newspaper. <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> publishes the Morning Advocate and State-Times newspapers in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>. The challenge contended that <PERSON> Livaudais </PERSON> should have given the reporters a chance to argue in favor of conducting open-court hearings and that he was required to tell why it was necessary to conduct the hearings in secret. The 5th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last July 31 upheld the closed hearings. The appeals court noted that past <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings have established a public right of access to criminal trials but ruled that under that constitutional right `` no presumption of openness attaches to proceedings involving midtrial questioning of jurors.'' `` If the questioning of impaneled jurors were held in open court there is a substantial probability that what may have begun as a ` tempest in a teapot' will end in a mistrial, a hung jury or a reversal on appeal,'' the 5th Circuit court said. The news organizations then sought <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Times-Picayune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, 87-872.
