<HEAD>Ambush Near U.S.-Run Base Kills Nine Filipinos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist rebels ambushed and killed six Filipino sailors assigned to <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> base 10 miles from the U.S.-run installation, the military said today. Three civilians also died in the shootout. Philippine officials today urged President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to develop a unified negotiating strategy before talks on the future of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. One of the country's best-known rebel priests fled to <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION> island after he was wounded by comrades who learned he was planning to surrender, officials said today. The Philippine Constabulary said the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> sailors were traveling to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> Sunday when rebels opened fire on their land rover near the town of <LOCATION> Hermosa </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION> peninsula. Three civilians were killed in the cross fire during the 15-minute battle, the military said. There were no reports of rebel casualties. <PERSON> Subic </PERSON>, 50 miles west of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, is one of six installations technically under Philippine command but effectively under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> control. Communist rebels operate near both Subic and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, about 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. In October last year, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> extraction in coordinated attacks outside <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. Cabinet secretaries and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> told reporters after a two-hour meeting today with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </P