<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to reinstate charges against 36 people arrested outside the White House while protesting <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration domestic and foreign policies. The court, without comment, left intact rulings that dismissed the charges on grounds government prosecutors acted vindictively. A demonstration for `` peace, jobs and justice'' occurred April 22, 1985. About 200 participants were arrested. They were charged with violating the terms of their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Park Police march permit by sitting down on sidewalks outside the White House. Most of those arrested agreed to pay a $ 50 fine for demonstrating without a permit rather than stand trial. But 36 demonstrators chose to stand trial. They were charged _ in addition to demonstrating without a permit _ with obstructing the sidewalks adjacent to the White House. Each charge carries a maximum penalty of six months in prison and a $ 500 fine. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> ordered all charges against the 36 dismissed, ruling that prosecutors acted vindictively by bringing the second charge only for those who chose to stand trial. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s decision last year. The appeals court said there was ample evidence for <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> to conclude that prosecutors added the second charge to punish demonstrators for choosing to stand trial. `` A large group of defendants threatened to go to trial on what the government considered petty offenses,'' the appeals court said. `` The government had a strong incentive to try to keep clear of this courtroom morass. It wished to avoid the annoyance and expense of prosecuting these minor cases at a potentially drawn-out trial.'' Prosecutors showed a `` disturbing willingness to toy with the defendants,'' the appeals court added. It said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was justified in throwing out both charges against the 36 demonstrators, not merely the second accusation that they obstructed the sidewalks. `` If in cases of vindictive prosecution the trial court judge may only dismiss the additional charge, the prosecutor wil have nothing to lose by acting vindictively,'' the appeals court said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said the lower court rulings could `` significantly hamper'' the government's handling off mass demonstrations in the nation's capital. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, 87-730.
