<HEAD>Court Clears Way for Trial in California Rent-Control Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today cleared the way for a trial in what may become an important test case on the power of cities to control rents and otherwise protect mobile home residents. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, officials aimed at killing a lawsuit by the owners of a mobile home park who claim they unfairly are being deprived of their property's full value. A <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> ordinance adopted in 1984 requires mobile home park operators to offer their tenants leases of unlimited duration. It also permits a maximum yearly rent increase of 3 percent or three-fourths of the increase in the Consumer Price Index, whichever is greater. The ordinance was challenged by <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, who own the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amigos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estates </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>. They said their property is being `` taken'' without the `` just compensation'' required by the Constitution. The Halls argued that granting mobile home owners a perpetual lease allows them to sell the lease at a windfall profit. The windfall is due to the new owners' anticipation of continued low land rent at below-market rates, the Halls said. A federal judge threw out the suit, but the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated it in 1986. The appeals court noted that the Halls said the price of mobile homes in the park shot up dramatically after the ordinance was enacted, suggesting the guaranteed low rents were worth a premium to buyers. `` Reduced to its essentials,'' the appeals court said, the Halls' claim `` is that the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> ordinance has transferred a possessory interest in their land to each of their 71 tenants. This interest consists of the right to occupy the property in perpetuity while paying only a fraction of what it is worth in rent.'' The appeals court acknowledged that the ordinance allows mobile home owners to be removed if they do n't pay the rent or if they misbehave. That may ease the economic impact, the appeals court said, but it does not alter the basic right of possession given the home owners. The ordinance `` changes the fundamental relationship between the parties, giving landlord and tenant complementary estates in the same land,'' the appeals court said. The appeals court said a trial is necessary to determine if the Halls' allegations about a windfall are accurate. <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and other cities in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> joined in asking the high court to review the case. The cities are <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Capitola </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hayward </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Altos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> View </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Oxnard </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Rancho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirage </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Rialto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Buenaventura </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vacaville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vallejo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Westlake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>. The justices on Feb. 24 expanded the power of communities to impose rent controls by upholding a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, ordinance that allows hardships to tenants to be considered when landlords seek rent increases. The ordinance had been atttacked as a `` Robin Hood'' law that steals from the rich to pay the poor. The case is <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> vs. Hall, 87-220.
