<HEAD>Court Refuses to Hear Appeal of Jehovah's Witness in Florida Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to hear the appeal of a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> woman who says she was denied custody of her young child because she is a <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witness. The justices, without comment, let stand state court rulings that bar <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> from exposing her daughter to any of her religious beliefs. The state courts also awarded primary residential custody of the girl to her father. In the appeal acted on today, Mrs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> said her freedom-of-religion rights were violated by the custody determination. <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ignacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> were divorced in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in 1985, after a four-year marriage. Their daughter, <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>, was then 3. Marital difficulties arose in 1983 over Mrs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON>'s involvement with the <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witnesses religion Her husband is a Catholic who, according to court documents, felt his wife had `` betrayed him'' by joining the <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witnesses. At a custody trial, <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> testfieid that it was not in <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>'s best interest to be raised as a <ORGANIZATION> Jehovah </ORGANIZATION>'s Witness. Of the 485 pages in the divorce proceedings transcript devoted to child custody, 249 pages contain references to the subject of religion. Two psychologists and one psychiatrist testified that <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> should live with her mother, whom they called the child's `` prime parent figure.'' But the experts said contact with her mother's <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witness religion was not in <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>'s best interest because she needs `` to adapt herself to the mainstream of culture.'' They testified that a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> upbringing `` would allow her to adapt to society and have the freedom that <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> children have in the society.'' Judge <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, in awarding primary custody of <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> to her father, ruled that Mrs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> should enjoy `` regular, frequent and liberal visitation, access and contact with the minor child.'' But he also barred Mrs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> from exposing <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> to `` any religious practices, attendances, teachings or events which are in any way inconsistent with the religious teachings and practices of the Catholic religion.'' A state appeals court upheld the custody award, ruling that `` the record in this case does not support -LRB- Mrs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON>'s -RRB- contention that the trial court made the father the primary residential parent ... solely because the mother is a practicing <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witness.'' In a dissenting vote, one appeals court judge said granting the father primary custody amounted to `` an abuse of discretion.'' `` The child, exposed to the religious views of both parents for two years, showed no evidence of emotional or psychological harm,'' the judge said, adding that the custody proceedings showed `` the experts' personal biases against the mother's religion.'' `` Their disdain for the mother's religion induced them to speculate as to the possibility of harm to the child in the future even though no evidence of harm existed,'' the dissenting judge said. Lawyers for Mrs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> told the justices, `` This court can not eliminate religious bigotry in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> but it can and should review this decision, which has deprived a parent of her child because of intolerance of her faith.'' The appeal added, `` The trial court's order places <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> in the anomalous position of having a constitutionally protected right to speak to total strangers about her religion but not to her own child.'' The case is <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON>, 87-1166.
