<HEAD>Court Refuses to Allow Indian Tribe to Withhold Records in
Minnesota Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to allow an Indian tribe to withhold from federal officials confidential records of a tribal court proceeding. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that gave the government custody of court records of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Band </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chippewa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. The tribe in 1985 declared that records of proceedings before its court of Indian offenses are confidential and not the federal government's property. The Chippewas were concerned that if the documents were given to the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, the agency would be forced to surrender the material to a newspaper that sought the records under the Freedom of Information Act -LRB- FOIA -RRB-. Indian tribes are not covered by the <ORGANIZATION> FOIA </ORGANIZATION> and may not be forced directly to reveal confidential information to the news media. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last August that the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> is entitled to the material. The appeals court rejected arguments by the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Band </LOCATION> that only <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could grant the government access to the records, and ruled that the government has sovereignty over tribal courts despite the absence of specific congressional authorization. The considerable independence given tribes to govern themselves does not mean they have the power automatically to withhold information from the government, the appeals court said. The Red Lake Band court of Indian offenses was established in 1884 under authority granted to the tribe by federal officials. The 8th Circuit court said that if the <LOCATION> Chippewa </LOCATION> court had been created under a later federal statute, the Indian Reorganization Act of 1934, the confidential records might be exempt from federal control. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Band </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-950.
