<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Pennsylvania Law on Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to reinstate a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law forcing state police officers to retire at age 60. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the state law violates federal restrictions against discrimination based on age. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last June that <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> violated the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act. The appeals court said it is illegal to presume that officers over 60 are physically unfit for their work when officials have failed to adopt minimum fitness standards for all workers. `` Until minimum standards are developed, implemented and enforced, the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> State Police can not justify its mandatory retirement law by relying on good health and physical conditioning as ... reasonably necessary to <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> business,'' the appeals court said. The appeals court noted that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, a neighboring state of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, has a mandatory retirement age of 55 for state troopers that has been upheld in the courts. But the appeals court said, `` All members of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> are subject to mandatory fitness requirements and are sanctioned for non-compliance.'' The federal law against age bias generally permits employers to force workers to retire before 70 only if it can be shown that being under 70 is a bona fide occupational qualification or if employers can prove it is highly impractical to test workers individually to assure they are still fit. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a pair of 1985 rulings that reinforced the employment rights of older workers, struck down efforts to force city firefighters to retire at age 55 and flight engineers at age 60. The 3rd Circuit court cited those cases in invalidating <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s mandatory retirement age for state police officers. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> officials said the appeals court ruling places a heavy financial burden on the state. The state said it could be forced to pay $ 4 million in back pay and benefits to officers who have been forced to retire. Officials also said that testing state police officers for fitness would be a costly process. They said it would cost some $ 2.4 million to determine whether the force's 4,000 members are healthy and fit. The state said its retirement-age policy is reasonable because of statistics that show a sharp decline in average fitness and health for older people. For example, the state said the decrease in aerobic capacity for an average group of men aged 26 and an average group of men age 58 is 57 percent. Relative strength declines by about 35 percent between the ages of 29 and 50 and muscular endurance slips by 30 percent between ages 30 and 60, the officials said. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s retirement law was challenged by the federal <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Binker </PERSON>, a lieutenant on the state police force who was near age 60 in 1983 when the suit was filed. The case is <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, 87-958.
