<HEAD>City Says Boys' Tree House Must Go</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURG, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Potential liability problems surrounding a tree house that extends two feet over public property have prompted city officials to give the structure the ax. `` It's accessible to the public, and there is the possibility it could entirely or partially fall on somebody passing by or damage property,'' said Chief Building Inspector <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kidwell </PERSON>. The 8-by-6-foot tree house was built by <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Macdonald </PERSON>'s father, a contractor, a few months ago as a Christmas present for her sons, <PERSON> James </PERSON>, 6, and <PERSON> Joey </PERSON>, 4 It features wall-to-wall carpeting, a shingled roof and sliding plexiglass windows and is a popular place for neighborhood children to play. `` If I did n't have school, I'd spend every single day up there,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Macdonald </PERSON>. `` My dad said, ` Whatever happened to the days of <PERSON> Huckleberry </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>?''' said <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Macdonald </PERSON>. She said she understands the city's concern but added that few people use the sidewalk on their dead-end street. `` I've been up there on the windiest days and nothing has happened,'' she said. `` We'd have to have an earthquake or a nuclear war.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Macdonalds </ORGANIZATION> have until March 21 to remove the tree house. If the city does n't change its mind, they will build a foundation for it in their back yard and place it there.
