<HEAD>PM-Scotus-Negotiations,700</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in an important victory for investors, today placed a heavy burden of proof on companies that are sued for denying they are holding merger negotiations after such preliminary talks are underway. By a 4-2 vote, the court said if companies withhold important information affecting stock prices, it must be presumed that investors who bought and sold the securities were relying on that information. `` An investor who buys or sells stock at the price set by the market does so in reliance on the integrity of that price,'' said Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> for the court. `` Because most publicly available information is reflected in market price, an investor's reliance on any public material misrepresentations, therefore, may be presumed. The absence of a five-vote majority in the case raises the possibility the issue could be reconsidered by the justices in another case with a different result. But, for now at least, today's decision is likely to have important repercussions on Wall Street. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who joined the court last month, did not take part in considering the case. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> disqualified themselves from participating without explanation. The court ordered further hearings in a dispute involving <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. The company merged with <ORGANIZATION> CEBAS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of Combustion Engineering based in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, in December 1978. Stockholders said Basic executives falsely denied for 14 months prior to the merger that at least preliminary talks were underway between the two companies. As a result, many investors said they sold their stock at far less than its value. Combustion Engineering is a conglomerate that makes alumina or acid-based refractories _ non-metallic ceramic substances used as structural materials. Both Basic and Combustion Engineering were traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The stock of Basic was selling at well under $ 20 a share when merger rumors began surfacing in late 1977. There was a dramatic increase in the volume of activity in the stock accompanied by a sharp run-up in price. The eventual merger price of the stock was $ 46 a share. Company officials repeatedly said they could not account for the activity and denied merger negotiations were underway. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1986 that public statements by Basic management during the period leading up to the merger were misleading or untrue, even if the company's denials of negotiations might be correct technically. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected the appellate court's reasoning that the company's denial of the preliminary talks by itself created grounds for the investors to win their suit. Information about a company that is otherwise insignificant does not become important _ or material to the stock's value _ solely because the company denied existence of the development, <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said. `` Materiality is something to be determined on the basis of the particular facts of each case,'' <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said. `` Materiality depends on the significance the reasonable investor would place on the withheld or misrepresented information.'' Using that standard, the court ordered further lower court hearings in the suit by investors in Basic who said they lost money because facts were withheld from them. <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said the presumption at the new hearings must be that the investors would have relied on those facts, unless the management of Basic can prove otherwise. `` Where materially misleading statements have been disseminated into an impersonal, well-developed market for securities, the reliance of individual plaintiffs on the integrity of the market price may be presumed,'' <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said. He was joined by Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, in an opinion joined by Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, said the ruling `` may have many adverse, unintended effects as it is applied and interpreted in the years to come.'' For example, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said many investors in Basic who are now suing may have doubted the company's denials that preliminary merger talks were underway. `` Such investors, the savviest of the savvy, will be able to recover under the court's opinion,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Levinson </PERSON>, 86-279.
</TEXT>
