<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 British soldiers and police shot and killed three unarmed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> members and Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> today a `` dreadful terrorist act has been averted.'' News reports said two men and a woman were killed Sunday after they planted a car bomb and set it to go off Tuesday during a military parade in this British colony. But <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> denied the news reports and said no bomb had been planted. He said a second car linked to the guerrillas and parked in <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> territory near border with <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>, a British colony, contained three false passports and equipment, including an alarm clock, insulating tape, gloves and wire. `` There is no doubt whatever that as a result of yesterday's events a dreadful terrorist act has been averted,'' said <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, speaking to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> `` The three people killed were actively involved in the planning and attempted excecution of that act.'' He did not elaborate. British news reports said the two men and a woman were killed after authorities uncovered a plot to set off the car bomb. The reports quoted unidentified security sources. The reports said bomb-disposal experts defused 440 pounds of explosives in a Spanish-registered car parked near Gov. Sir <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>'s official residence in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>, on the southern tip of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. British Armed Forces Minister <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said `` an intelligence tip-off'' led to information about the three memb