Authors Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs, material from news conference; picks up
4th graf pvs, ``Excerpts from...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two noted sex experts who criticized health authorities for failing to stress the extent of the AIDS epidemic said today that their own estimates of the spread of AIDS were based on beliefs and estimates, not scientific evidence. `` We did not project our own database on to the general population,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON>, co-author with <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Masters </PERSON> and <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of `` Crisis: Heterosexual Behavior in the Age of AIDS.'' <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON> said at a press conference this morning that the authors' assertion that AIDS is `` now running rampant in the heterosexual community'' was an estimate based on analysis of existing studies that have appeared in scientific journals. It was not based on original research by the authors, he said. Masters, asked for his justification of the claim, said, `` I simply believe it.'' The authors criticized health authorities for failing to stress the threat of AIDS to heterosexuals, and they have themselves been criticized by an AIDS expert for making recommendations that might alarm the public. But in their book Masters, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON> say that medical experts have played down their findings rather than present worst-case scenarios `` in the understandable wish to avoid mass panic.'' The book calls for widespread mandatory testing for acquired immune deficiency syndrome infection by pregnant women, couples seeking marriage licenses and hospital patients between ages 15 and 60. Excerpts from the book are appearing in this week's issue of Newsweek magazine. The authors run the Masters and <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and wrote a best-seller, `` Human Sexual Response.'' But some AIDS experts questioned their conclusions on the spread of the deadly disease. `` Masters and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> may have expertise in sexuality but they have no credentials to justify their recommendations concerning AIDS public health policy _ recommendations that will surely alarm the public,'' said <PERSON> Mathilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Krim </PERSON>, founding chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for AIDS Research. `` From everything we know today, such mandatory testing schemes will not help protect the public,'' she said Saturday. Masters and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s book suggests that to guard against infection, potential sexual partners undergo tests and remain monogamous. Dr. <PERSON> Beny </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Primm </PERSON>, a member of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s AIDS commission, said he agreed that recent optimistic reports about heterosexuals could `` lull people into a state of complacency.'' He said as a result many `` do n't use condoms, still are promiscuous and still participate in group sex or other dangerous activities.'' The book disputed estimates that there are now about 1.5 million people infected with the virus in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` It is quite likely that there are now 3 million or more carriers of the AIDS virus in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, most of whom are otherwise healthy and unaware of their infected, contagious state,'' it said. `` Experts generally are gravely underestimating the degree to which the AIDS virus has spread into the heterosexual community,'' it said. The authors said they based their findings on their own study of 800 sexually active heterosexual adults between the ages of 21 and 40 who met three criteria: no blood transfusions received since 1977; no use of illicit drugs by injection; no homosexual or bisexual contact since 1977. The study, however, did not appear to follow the usual scientific process and the authors conceded that their sample was not obtained by random sampling methods and did not closely match the general <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population. They said they found that among a subgroup of subjects who average more than 12 partners annually and generally failed to take precautions, 14 percent of the women had been infected with the AIDS virus and 12 percent of the men. The findings were an indication, the researchers said, that'' public health authorities have failed to impress the general public with the message that AIDS has broken out.
</TEXT>
