<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Eccentrics     03-07 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Eccentrics,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eccentric: A Perfectly Sane Way To Be, Researcher Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who hunt vampires, live in caves or slide down buildings in pink elephant costumes are n't crazy. They're just eccentric, and more creative than everybody else, says a researcher who spent three years studying them. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeks </PERSON>, principal clinical psychologist at the <LOCATION> Royal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, interviewed 130 eccentrics and said he found only one insane person in the crowd. He has turned his findings into a book called `` Eccentrics: The Scientific Investigation,'' to be published in May by <ORGANIZATION> Stirling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was the first scientific study of its kind in the world,'' Weeks said in a telephone interview Monday. His study exploded a few myths _ among them that Britons are more eccentric than Americans. `` <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has more of a reputation'' for eccentricity, said Weeks, an American from <LOCATION> Garwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who has lived in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since 1975. But both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> seem to have more eccentrics than other countries, possibly because they have the strongest traditions of free speech, according to Weeks. It's also a myth that British eccentrics are mainly aristocrats. `` They're mostly in the upper middle class _ professional people,'' the psychologist said, and they tend to be outspoken loners. Weeks cites <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> as an eccentric, given his interest in unconventional medicine, his habit of talking to plants, his solitary trips to meditate and his peevish outbursts against modern architecture. `` He'd probably be a lot more eccentric if he were n't royalty,'' the psychologist said. `` That probably restricts him.'' Weeks reckons one person in 10,000 is an eccentric. They tend to be highly creative and have vivid imaginations and graphic dreams. `` They have lots of good ideas,'' Weeks said. `` However, they can be inflexible. If they get a good idea, they stick with it.'' The eccentrics Weeks met included a man who has lived in a cave for eight years. Another eccentric scales office buildings in a pink elephant costume and has built a `` helimobile,'' a contraption with wheels, wings, flashing lights and an engine. `` It moves, but it does n't fly,'' Weeks said. Then there was a teacher from <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, who set up a vampire investigation bureau, which is open at night. The teacher travels the world hunting the bloodthirsty creatures. And a Scottish lady offered herself as a virgin sacrifice in a mock ritual atop a extinct volcano in the middle of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>. Only one turned out to be insane, Weeks said. He thought he was a secret agent and demonstrated a throat-cutting technique on Week' research assistant, <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, with a set of keys Weeks and Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> found eccentrics by word of mouth and publicity about their work. People who thought they qualified as eccentrics were given mental and personality tests. Eccentrics tend to be happier than most people because they do n't take themselves too seriously, Weeks said. `` They just have this good sense of humor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
