<HEAD>`Siamese Shrimp' Finds Place In Smithsonian Collection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A two-headed shrimp a fisherman found in his bait bucket appears to be the first such specimen on record, experts say. `` We're dealing with a first occurrence here, I guess, to the best of our knowledge,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ecology division in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>. The shrimp has been sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraley </PERSON>, 37 and his wife, <PERSON> C.J. </PERSON>, were fishing near <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> last May when <PERSON> Fraley </PERSON> dipped into his bait bucket and came out with the oddity. `` I said: ` Why, this thing's got two heads!''' he said. The couple photographed the shrimp, then took it home and put it in their freezer. Mrs. <PERSON> Fraley </PERSON> mentioned it to <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON>, who told <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a curator of invertebrates at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was as curious to me as it was to the folks who found it,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> dissected the shrimp and said both heads appeared normal in many ways. He has searched scientific literature to the late 1800s, but has found no mention of a similar case. <PERSON> Fraley </PERSON> feels lucky to have found the creature. `` I was excited,'' he said. `` And to think I nearly tore the head off.''
