<HEAD>Rackets Run Rampant In Mobster-Riddled Republic, Pravda Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corruption is so rampant in the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION> that a powerful underworld has developed, complete with hit men, protection rackets, police payoffs and powerful mob chieftains, Pravda said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper even noted that the funeral of an underworld crime boss drew 400 mourners. Pravda said many police officers not only looked the other way at crime in the Central Asian republic, but masterminded some of the schemes. It said 12 are now are on trial for extortion. `` They extorted money mostly from those who would n't appeal to the police, like a certain <PERSON> Gavrush </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarkisya </PERSON>, a former shop foreman, who confessed to the police later that he owed the criminals -LRB- $ 150,000 -RRB-,'' Pravda said. `` And they threatened him with a firing squad should he fail to pay up.'' Other Central Asian republics also have been blasted by the Soviet media for large-scale corruption. In recent months, the media have exposed millions of dollars in graft in <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION>'s neighbor to the north. On Jan. 20, the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Literaturnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> disclosed that the head of an agricultural complex in <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> built his own mob empire, complete with his own courts and an underground prison constructed by 1,000 workers. The expose was striking in its recitation of abuses. Pravda's account on <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION>, while not as dramatic, was the strongest criticism yet of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s southernmost republic, which has 3.27 million people, mostly Moslems. Official media criticism of <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION> usually has centered around Moslem customs judged by the central government to be abhorent, such as reports of young women being kill