<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said today it has protested poor maintenance of some <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal facilities, but said the problem was not linked to the recent political turmoil there. `` There are some facilities that are maintained by <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> that we have protested in a sense of not being adequately maintained,'' said <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. He said the complaint was registered `` sometime previously'' and was not intended to justify an abrogation of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaty. Meanwhile, a newspaper reported that political appointees installed by the Panamanian government are mismanaging operations of the canal that have been turned over by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Any user of those facilities will tell you there are difficulties now that simply did not exist 10 years ago,'' an unidentified Panamanian economist told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. Among the facilities suffering from mismanagement are ports, marine bunkering installations, a railroad, a bridge and air traffic control, according to the Times, which interviewed canal employees and shipping experts. `` This government has put a political aspect to an equation that has no room for politics,'' said a Panamanian engineer who has worked at the canal for more than a decade. `` As soon as you start to mix Panamanian politics with the running of the canal, that is the end of things.'' The country's political situation has been particularly troubled in recent weeks. Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the military leader who is <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s de facto leader, engineered the ou