<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lashed out today at congressional opponents to <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> aid, accusing them of a lack of courage in the battle against communism in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In a speech to the Veterans of Foreign Wars convention, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> talked about the votes last week in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that left the rebels battling the leftist government of <LOCATION> Nicragua </LOCATION> without <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> funding. The 216-208 vote defeated a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> plan to provide $ 30.8 million in food, clothing and medical aid to the rebels. The vote was scheduled by the Democratic leadership so the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> could not vote on an aid plan favored by the Republicans. `` Courage has n't exactly been the watchword of some opponents of Contra aid,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` ... Last week, aid opponents tried to pass the buck of responsibility for abandoning in the field the young men and women of the Democratic resistance, and that ploy failed as it should have.'' Administration officials have expressed the hope <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could come up with an alternative plan to keep the rebels alive as a fighting force. After <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> acknowledged that a `` real problem'' exists for the administration because a new Contra aid package might not be considered for some time. `` It's just a matter of time,'' he said. `` We will produce a package,'' he vowed at another point. In his speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recalled that Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> dismissed Cardinal <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> as the mediator in peace talks with the rebels. `` You know where <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> stands. Is n't it time for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to have the courage to show where it stands?'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked rhetorically. `` Now it's time for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to show that it knows you ca n't have real peace negotiations when one side has helicopter gunships and the other has bandages,'' he said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the defeat of the Contras would mean a `` grave strategic defeat for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' `` The communists in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> understand this, the Soviets understand this _ it's time that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> understood it, too,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, adding, `` A Soviet base on the American mainland is a pistol pointed at the heart of the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> contended that the `` real issue'' before the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is not the Contras, `` it is communisim in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The president, who was warmly greeted by the audience of older veterans, told them of his recent trip to <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, where he met with <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders. He asked their support for the ratification of the recently signed U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missles from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to reject further cuts in the nation's defense budget and allow for a strong alliance defense. `` This is not the time to drop our guard,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` It's just this simple If we put Americans in harm's way, we owe them the best weapons money can buy.'' `` We'll need to keep up our strength if we're to succeed, and that's why the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must not further reduce the defense budget,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. Offering a report on the <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> meeting in his Saturday radio address, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> declared that `` arms reduction is not enough'' in dealing with the Soviets and demanded they abandon the `` offensive strategy'' displayed against the Western alliance on the European continent. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said there was a `` lesson learned'' at the meeting, which was the first full-scale summit for the leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in six years. `` One must always negotiate with the Soviets from a position of strength,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. Following the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit, a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> advance team traveled to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to scout out possible sites for the fourth meeting between <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, planned for late May or early June. In his radio speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> pointed out that while the allies praised the new U.S.-Soviet agreement to remove all medium-range nuclear missiles from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, they reaffirmed the need to remain united and keep their guard up. `` That's why continued modernization of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> forces _ nuclear and conventional _ is essential,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said.
