<HEAD>Government Seeking Dismissal Of Suit To Bar Federal Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government is seeking the dismissal of a lawsuit that would end federal aid to religious schools abroad, primarily Jewish schools in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, a prosecutor said Monday. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Southern District, said he filed papers in federal court Friday arguing that the case ought to be dropped because the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> does not have `` standing,'' a legal term which means the right to bring the lawsuit. But <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a staff attorney the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the civil liberties group maintains that it can pursue the lawsuit because the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> represents <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> taxpayers whose money is used for the schools. The <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> has until March 24 to respond. The lawsuit stemmed from reports last December that Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, had persuaded his colleagues to allocate $ 8 million to build schools in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for North African Jews. The program provoked a firestorm of criticism, prompting <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to rescind the money. Lawmakers agreed to <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>'s wish After President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the bill killing the $ 8 million program last month, the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> amended its complaint to cover Jewish and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> schools that receive money under the American Schools and Hos