Silkworm missiles to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The tradeoff _ and at least Chinese neutrality in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drive to impose an international arms embargo against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> _ looms as the potential highlight of the talks <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> opened today. It is his first visit in four years, and the agenda is substantial. For instance, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> will solicit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s support for his proposal for <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace talks. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is trying to structure a peace conference in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> would serve as sponsors, but without the power to impose terms of a settlement. That calls for some delicate diplomacy. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is walking a tightrope between <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on the subject. King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> refuses to negotiate unless he has Big Power support. But Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> refuses to allow <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> or the Soviets, who usually support Arab positions, to take an active role. <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> arrived Sunday, had dinner with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and sees him and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> separately today. On Tuesday, the Chinese foreign minister calls on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the White House and meets with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> again. The shipping war in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> is uppermost in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> minds. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> may be <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s largest arms supplier. Sales last year were worth an estimated $ 1 billion. The most dangerous of the weapons are Silkworm missiles _ short-range rockets that even in unskilled hands can wreak havoc on merchant ships. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has used them effectively. Despite <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appeals, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> persisted in delivering installments of the Silkworms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> last year _ and denied what <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said it was doing. Frustrated, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> retaliated in October by suspending a decade-old process of liberalizing the types of high technology American companies could sell to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Since then, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has said it has stopped selling Silkworms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, speaking Friday on condition of anonymity, said `` our information is that they've been living up to that.'' Still, before resuming liberalization of the high-technology trade, `` we want to be sure we're in sync with the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> on what we're talking about,'' the official said. `` We want to be sure that this responsiveness will continue.'' On an arms embargo, meanwhile, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> would like a commitment from Wu that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would not veto a resolution in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to impose a worldwide arms embargo against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The sanctions would enforce a cease-fire resolution adopted last July that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> accepted but <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> scorned. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> experts believe <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would at least remain neutral if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed not to veto the resolution. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been after <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> since July for support, but is not sure it has it yet.
