<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been embarassed in space research since the Challenger disaster, and risks forfeiting its edge in high technology and other fields unless it expands space-based scientific missions, a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> official and researchers told a congressional hearing Monday. Further delays in projects already backed up three years plus a lack of funding for new space experiments will allow the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and European nations to cement the lead they have taken over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since the Challenger explosion, said <PERSON> Lennard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>, associate administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` A lead that we had was allowed to erode and now we have to ask ourselves where we are going,'' said <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>, who outlined the science-related portion of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed fiscal 1989 budget to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee on Science, Technology and Space. <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said 20 major science-related payloads are scheduled to be carried into space in the next four years, half of them aboard space shuttles and half on expendable rockets. The projects include probes to <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> and Jupiter and the launching of an X-ray telescope, space telescope and gamma ray observatory designed to work in tandem to study a number of phenomena, including a supernova that occurred last year. The new X-ray telescope, the Advanced X-Ray Astrophysics Facility, should also help researchers determine what the universe looked like up to 20 billion years ago and produce dramatic improvements in pharmaceuticals and computer chips, said Dr. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Tananbaum </PERSON> of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics. Resumption of the shuttle program and approval of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s science-related budget is vital to getting the 20 projects launched by 1993 and to prove to commercial businesses which pay to have satellites and experiments carried into space that the <LOCATION> Unites </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will re-establish itself as a dominant force in space, <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said He also urged researchers to develop new space-based experiments and technology so that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> can begin planning missions past 1993, when it is scheduled to complete current projects. `` We have a hiatus in space science launches today because of the Challenger tragedy,'' <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said. `` Let us not create another hiatus in the mid-1990s by failing to start major flight projects now.'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., a subcommittee member who presided over the hearing, said a revitalized space program also was vital to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> businesses and universities, which received 846 contracts totaling $ 413 million in 1987 and have to date in 1988 been awarded 710 contracts totaling $ 388 million <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> and the academicians told the subcommittee that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> should not be pressured to curtail manned missions with civilian researchers because of the January 1986 Challenger explosion that killed seven astronauts, including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> teacher <PERSON> Christa </PERSON> <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akin </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, said that while computers and robots can greatly contribute to space research, their advancement should not be used to support calls for an end to manned space flights. `` Exploration is one of the last jobs which should be turned over to robots, as the curiosity for thirst and knowledge underlying the urge to explore is one of the finest attributes of being human,'' Akin said. `` Let us instead spend our efforts getting humans out of mine shafts and off high steel construction sites. Robots should totally replace man in the worst of jobs, not the best.''
