<HEAD>International Conference Focuses On Making Cities More Liveable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of experts from around the globe gather in antebellum <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> this week to seek ways to make the world's cities better places to live. The 4th International Conference on Making Cities Liveable, which opens Wednesday, is being held in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for the first time. `` The quality of life in our cities has become increasingly a national concern,'' Mayor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> boasts many `` important national, if not international, examples of the liveability of cities,'' from its preservation efforts to its innovative programs of low-income housing to the acclaimed <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> arts festival. `` But we have so much to learn,'' he said. `` It's a conference for people who are concerned about the quality of life in the city'' but is n't a professional conference, said <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennard </PERSON>, one of the organizers and a founder of the Center for Urban Well-Being. `` It brings together many different kinds of people. It brings together city planners and architects, city council presidents and mayors and citizens who are simply concerned about making their cities more liveable,'' she said. More than 300 people are expected to attend and more than 100 people are scheduled to speak. Among the topics of discussion will be the design of public spaces, festivals, the role of markets in the city and a number of case studies. The Center for Urban Well-Being, based in <LOCATION> Southhampton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, is a partnership that conducts research, publishes and works with cities on urban issues. The first three international conferences were held in <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>. `` We wanted to bring it to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to make it more accessible for Am