<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No order is too tall for Richlee Shoes, which specializes in elevator shoes. It even sells elevator bedroom slippers. `` If you're going to be taller at the office and the company picnic, why would n't you want to be taller at home? Wo n't the neighbors notice if you run out to get the paper that you're shorter? said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, who operates the company with his sister and three brothers. Ninety styles, priced $ 40 to $ 120, are displayed in 100,000 square feet of warehouse space just south of <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON>. It sells direct and through mail order. `` We do n't feel we've even scratched the surface'' of the number of men who want to appear taller, said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. `` Depending on the style, our shoes can make a man two inches taller. I've had people call me up ... they say ` the difference in my height has made a difference in my social life.''' Elevator shoes have come a long way from the days when the company's celebrity spokesman, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON>, sported oxfords with chunky heels that did n't hide their purpose. Today's elevator shoes look like normal shoes but have a built-up insole. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he even has one regular customer who stands 6-foot-5. `` I asked him why,'' he said. `` He said he was a basketball player in college and all his friends were 6-feet-7 or 8.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MAITLAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A self-cleaning bathtub and salt dyed red so that people can know how much they use. Sunglasses with pockets and a life-preserver for horses. Those are inventions by kids involved in a program called Invent <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, which seeks to boost the level of creativity and innovation in this country. At <ORGANIZATION> Dommerich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in this <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> suburb, fifth-graders are brainstorming their way to new ideas to resolve problems, such as locating a dog at night or taking out the garbage. The Invent America class is taught by <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> one day a week to each of five classes of gifted students in different grades. He came from <ORGANIZATION> Ocoee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, which won four of <LOCATION> Invent </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s nine state awards, the most of any school in the country. `` We've just kind of forgotten to teach the children the old <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> ingenuity,'' says <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, 44. The program was started by the privately funded <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Model </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Besides opening up the innovative process, <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> says, the program enhances students' self-esteem. One Ocoee second-grader who was emotionally and mentally disturbed and had no friends invented a device that earned him his classmates' admiration. `` Suddenly he became a famous inventor. He just became a totally different individual,'' <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> said. The problem of finding a dog at night was addressed by 11-year-old <PERSON> Seth </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, who plans to develop a dog collar with a light attached before the class ends with a school fair in April. Ten-year-old <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cadle </PERSON> hates carrying the garbage cans out so much that he concentrated all his efforts on that one issue. His solution? Motorized garbage cans that can be driven from the house to the street, and back.
