<HEAD>Court To Decide Case On Disqualifying Black Potential Jurors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will decide whether a criminal defendant's right to a jury selected from a cross-section of the community is violated when prosecutors disqualify potential jurors because they are black. The court will review the case of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>, sentenced to 30 years in prison for the armed robbery of a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> supermarket and for the attempted murder of police officers shot at after the robbery. The justices in 1986 ruled in a case called <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> that prosecutors never may disqualify potential jurors based on their race. The court said such tactics violate equal-protection rights. But a subsequent decision strictly limited the retroactive effect of the <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> ruling. The court said the <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> decision does not apply to convicted criminals who, like <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>, had exhausted direct appeals in state courts prior to April 30, 1986, when <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> was announced. If the justices were to rule that the prosecutorial tactics used at <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>'s trial violated his Sixth Amendment right to cross-sectional jury selection, he would be entitled to a new trial even though the <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> ruling came too late to help him. Presumably, such a ruling would affect other prison inmates' convictions as well The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last May that past <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions make clear that `` the fair cross-section requirement of the Sixth Amendment does not apply to the jury itself'' but only to the pool of potential jurors from which juries are chosen. Lawyers for <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>, who is black, contend that his fair-trial rights were violated when prosecutors used all 10 of their so-called peremptory challenges to exclude blacks from the jury. The court's decision is not expected until sometime in 1989.
