<FIRST>r w AM-ConsumerCredit     03-07 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Credit,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>January Marks Biggest Debt Increase In Four Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans took out $ 5.42 billion more in installment debt than they paid off in January, the biggest monthly increase in four months and the second strong month in a row, the government said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said consumer credit grew at a seasonally adjusted rate of 10.6 percent in January, following an increase of $ 3.98 billion in December, which translated to an annual rate of 7.9 percent. Growth in both months was greater than the 5.9 percent rate for all of 1987, which represents a considerable slowdown compared with recent years. The rate was 10.5 percent in 1986. The relatively strong January report is both a reflection of job growth _ unemployment hit a nine-year low of 5.7 percent in February _ and a sign that the rebound in consumer confidence after the October stock market crash is continuing, according to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm. `` What we're seeing right now ... is a sort of soft landing for consumer spending,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, whose firm is predicting growth between 6.5 percent and 7 percent this year. `` We're not really looking for a recession to occur, if anything just a bit of slowness in the first half of the year.'' The January increase was the biggest advance since debt rose by $ 6.43 billion in September. The gains in both months were strongly influenced by an upturn in car sales. Auto loans rose by $ 1.54 billion in January, an annual rate of 7.1 percent, and followed a stronger gain of 10.7 percent in December. Credit card and revolving loans grew by $ 2.0 billion in January, a 16.5 percent annual rate, following an increase of 19.3 percent a month earlier. The debt category which includes bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate grew by $ 1.73 billion, an 11.6 percent growth rate, following a decline of 3.5 percent in December. Loans for mobile homes increased $ 142 million after falling $ 122 million in December. The various changes left total consumer debt at $ 617.5 billion in January.
