<HEAD>High Court To Rule Whether Stereotyping Denied Woman Partnership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday set the stage for an important ruling on sex discrimination, agreeing to study a case in which `` unconscious stereotyping'' allegedly played a key role in denying a woman an accounting firm partnership. The justices said they will review a ruling that places a heavy burden on employers to disprove sex bias. Arguments in the case will be heard in the fall during the court's next term and a decision is not likely to be announced until 1989. Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's largest accounting firms, is accused of discriminating unlawfully against <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>. She quit the firm's office here after she was denied promotion to partnership, a move that would have made her a part owner. Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> joined the firm in 1978 and was nominated for partnership in 1982, the only woman among 88 candidates for partnership that year. She had been very successful in getting business for the company, winning government contracts worth an estimated $ 34 million to $ 44 million. Of the 88 candidates, 47 were invited to become partners; 21 were rejected outright; and 20 including Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> were placed on hold. The following year she was told she would not become a partner, and she resigned in 1984 to set up her own consulting firm. Both her critics and supporters at Price Waterhouse said she sometimes was overly aggressive, too harsh, impatient with her staff and very demanding. One critic suggested she needed to take a `` course at charm school.'' A partner in the firm who urged her promotion told her she would stand a better chance of becoming a partner if she would `` walk more femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear make-up, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.'' Others said her use of profanity was a black mark against her. Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> then sued Price Waterhouse, accusing the company of violating Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibiting on-the-job sex disscrimination. She said that sex stereotyping, unconscious or otherwise, barred her from being named partner. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1984, in the case of a woman denied partnership in a law firm, that professional partnerships are covered by the 1964 law. A federal judge ruled Price Waterhouse must prove `` by clear and convincing evidence'' it would not have made her a partner regardless of whether sexual stereotyping played a part in its decision. Price Waterhouse said it was unable to provide such proof. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here last August said there is `` competent evidence that ... the partnership selection process at Price Waterhouse was impermissibly infected by stereotypical attitudes toward female candidates.'' The appeals court said even if there is evidence that Ms. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>' personality played a part in her denial of partnership, Price Waterhouse is unable to prove `` impermissible bias was not the determinative factor.'' The appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what back pay and other remedies the company must provide. The case is Price Waterhouse vs. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, 87-1167.
