ed fuels program, which was launched for the first time in January and lasted two months, required all service stations along the 130-mile corridor along the <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Range </ORGANIZATION> between <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collins </ORGANIZATION> to sell only oxygenated fuels, or fuels containing at least 1.5 percent oxygen. The program's purpose was to provide a gasoline that would burn cleaner in car engines and thus contribute less carbon monoxide pollution, officials said. Motorists were offered the choice of an ether-gasoline blend, or gasohol, which contains ethyl alcohol. <PERSON> Grady </PERSON> said the oxy fuels program was right on target in its goal of reducing ambient carbon-monoxide levels by 8 percent to 10 percent. The reduction was in the 8 percent to 9.5 percent range, she said.
