<SECOND>AM-Condor Egg,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Keepers Detect The Beginnings Of A Condor Chick</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condor egg produced by captive breeding is fertile and contains the makings of a chick, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> Wild Animal Park officials said Monday. `` You ca n't actually see an embryo yet, but what you can see is the beginnings of circulatory development, which appears as a dark dime-sized dot toward the top of the yolk,'' park spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanscom </PERSON> said. The egg was laid Thursday, the product of a male condor known as AC-4 and a female condor called UN-1. It was removed immediately from its nest in the park's `` condorminium'' and placed in an incubator. Keepers peeked inside the egg by holding it up to a high-intensity lamp in a process known as `` candling.'' The egg then was returned to its incubator, where it will be kept until the hatching expected between April 28 and May 3, <ORGANIZATION> Hanscom </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Now, we incubate the egg according to the parameters that have worked so well in the past and hope ... we can hatch a healthy condor chick,'' he said. All 27 living <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors are in captivity. Fourteen are kept at the Wild Animal Park and 13 at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Zoo. Thirteen of the 27 birds were hatched in captivity in an effort to build a breeding flock to save the rare birds from extinction. Each of those eggs were taken from nests in the wild. The breeding program has been conducted at the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> and its affiliate, the Wild Animal Park, since 1983 in cooperation with state and federal wildlife officials. The last known wild condor was captured in April 1987 by government biologists after it was determined the carrion-eating birds' existence was threatened by lead poisoning in their food supply and human encroachment upon their central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> habitat. `` Our success or failure has pivoted on the captive production of a fertile egg and that's what we've got,'' <ORGANIZATION> Hanscom </ORGANIZATION> said of the 4-day-old egg. Meanwhile, the parents of the egg were said to be doing well. Keepers removed the shell from its nest soon after it was laid to stimulate more breeding activity by the pair, which <ORGANIZATION> Hanscom </ORGANIZATION> said has begun. `` That's real positive,'' he said. `` That would lead us to hope for the production of a second egg, which could come as early as 30 days after the first egg. `` The parents are doing fine, the egg is doing fine and the keepers are doing fine.''
</TEXT>
