<FIRST>r a AM-FloridaCrime     03-07 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Crime,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number Of Serious Crimes Rise By 6.3 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 1 million serious crimes were reported in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> last year, a record number blamed in part on the spread of `` crack'' cocaine and other drugs, authorities announced Monday. The number of reported homicides, rapes, robberies, assaults, burglaries, larcenies and motor vehicle thefts rose 6.3 percent to go over the 1 million mark for the first time, to 1,021,283, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON>, commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION>. `` As you know, the crime rate is driven to a large extent by the drug problem. There is no question about that,'' <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> said. He urged Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to consider increasing spending for criminal justice. Presently, he said, 6 percent of an $ 18.5 billion budget is devoted to the criminal justice system, which includes law enforcement and the courts, he said. `` It's intolerable. We need to do something about addressing credibility in the criminal justice area,'' <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> said. `` We need to address the career criminals, the jail situation and some of the weaknesses in the so-called criminal justice system, which as many of you know is no system at all.'' <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> also said citizens need to start a grassroots campaign to help prevent violence and property thefts. Increases in property crime, particularly in some of the more rural counties, can be directly attributed to the increase of the powerful crack form of cocaine, the commissioner said. `` Anybody who tells you the drug problem is leveling off is in fairyland. They do n't know what's happening,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> figures released Monday were preliminary. A complete report was expected to be issued later this year. The commissioner said <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> continues to lead other states in crime rates, or the number of crimes reported per 100,000 population. He compared <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s 1987 figures with figures reported by other states in 1986. `` We have the highest crime rate in the nation,'' said <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON>. Department spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s per-capita crime rate, which increased by 2.9 percent in 1987, has been significantly higher in past years than the figures reported by other states. Since <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> is one of the first to release its figures, new data was unavailable in other states. In 1986, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> had 8,238 serious crimes reported per 100,000 population, compared with 7,408 in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 7,322 in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, 7,081 in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, 7,032 in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, 6,880 in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, 6,763 in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 6,626 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, 6,491.5 in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and 6,290 in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. The District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> actually had the highest of all with 8,339 per 100,000 population. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the total arrests for cocaine last year were up 32.8 percent over 1986, while property crimes increased 6.7 percent over 1986. The number of motor vehicle thefts rose by 16.4 percent, and aggravated assaults showed a 3.1 percent increase. The number of reported murders and rapes was slightly down. Homicides declined from 1,371 to 1,368 and rapes declined from 6,153 to 6,017. More police officers were assaulted and killed in 1987 than the previous year, 10 compared with six. Assaults on police officers rose from 7,289 in 1986 to 7,833 in 1987. <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> acknowledged that the overall crime increase was not as high as had been reported in recent years. From 1985 to 1986, his department reported a 7.9 percent increase. The increase was 11.4 percent from 1984 to 1985. `` It's true the rate of increase is dropping but it is still an increase,'' <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
