 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> opened his bid for a third, six-year term on Monday, describing himself as a fighter and warning backers to brace for negative ads and gutter politics from opponents. `` This battle that I'm about to embark upon today will be the toughest battle that I've ever experienced in my lifetime. I can not tell you all the details of all the stuff, and nonsense, and sleaze that they're pouring into <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, told an airport rally. `` I'm asking Ohioans to judge this campaign not on nasty, negative ads nor gutter politics. You'll see plenty of both thrown our way, and it's already started,'' said <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, who is being challenged by <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Voinovich </PERSON>, a Republican, in the Nov. 8 election. `` There are some powerful forces who want to see me out of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. For them no price is too high, no tactic is too low,'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said. The rally, which drew a crowd of about 100 that included officeholders and union members, was one of four as <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> barnstormed the state in a plane piloted by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, his campaign chairman. Other stops were in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>.
