<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Makes Sales Pitch on Economic Reform to Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has told factory workers not to be discouraged by slow improvements in their standard of living and to have faith in his overhaul of the economy. He visited the enormous <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ball </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bearing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, his first meeting with rank-and-file workers since a sweeping law took effect Jan. 1 giving factories more financial independence from central ministries. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he was particularly sensitive to complaints about poor housing and food and said they were top priorities for improvement. The 57-year-old Soviet leader visited the factory Friday but media did not report on the trip until Monday. Why the reports were delayed was not clear. `` Of course we have a sufficient number of problems,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the workers. `` Part of them are left from the past, others were born today, in the course of restructuring, in the process of realizing economic reforms. That's natural. But I have the impression that you have n't panicked, and I would say are optimistically looking to the future and confidently going forward.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has visited factories several times since becoming <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> general secretary three years ago, highlighting the importance he attaches to workers' roles in reviving the sluggish Soviet economy. The ball bearing plant employs 20,000 factory and office workers. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he wanted to get a first-hand look at how the government's new economic reforms are being implemented. `` For politics, the most important thing is to know the mood of the people, to feel the pulse of life,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in remarks carried by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. He explained to the workers why some of his economic policies may be hard to swallow, because they mean harder work and in some cases less pay. Salaries, he said, must be adjusted according to the productivity and quality of labor. `` How can you pay someone a full ruble if he has n't earned it? What will he buy with this money?'' he said. He said the reason desired goods have not been available in stores is that workers were guaranteed salaries whether or not they did their jobs properly. Under the new law, managers at factories responsible for 60 percent of the country's industrial output can bargain with suppliers and wholesale customers for some products. Enterprises are free to keep some of their profits, but those that are unsuccessful are liable to be declared bankrupt. The factories set workers' salaries according to the quality of their work. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> critcized plant managers who try to find an easy way out of improving output by buying foreign equipment. `` Obviously you must buy some things, but only that which is absolutely necessary, and you should rely on your own domestic machine-building, on the achievements of our engineering.'' He assured the workers socialism will not be threatened by the country's growing private enterprises, known as cooperatives. `` It's understood that we need industrious and honest initiative, but not of the kind of some cooperatives which exploit a deficit and engage in outright money-grabbing,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. Limited private enterprise has been allowed to supplement state-run enterprises since May 1987. Prices of the goods and services produced by cooperatives are generally much higher, but <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the workers the government plans to get its fair share of profits, through a progressive tax.
