<HEAD>Judge Bars INS from Routine Strip-Searching of Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Routine strip searches of children awaiting deportation are unconstitutional, a federal judge ruled Monday, saying immigration agents must first have a reasonable suspicion that drugs or weapons have been hidden. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON> rejected an Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> argument that the body-cavity searches are needed because adults will use children as couriers if agents can not search them. `` Children confined by the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> are not charged with any criminal offense, let alone an offense that might indicate a propensity to conceal weapons or contraband on their persons,'' <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON> ruled. In 1987, of 84,000 aliens searched, there were 20 discoveries of contraband or weapons, only four of which were related to juveniles, <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON> noted. His ruling came in a class-action suit filed in 1985 by a coalition of immigrants' rights groups that challenged what they described as routine strip-searches of children upon admission to <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> detention facilities and following all visits with anyone other than attorneys. Children are particularly susceptible to trauma from strip searches, <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON> said. He rejected an argument by Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Fan </PERSON> that children from <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> have no expectation of privacy when arrested here. `` Many carry the expectation of liberty, opportunity and a better life, the embodiment of which is our Constitution,'' <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON> wrote. Only children are affected by the ruling. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagar </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN