<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 S <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Nazi-hunting unit has identified 9,800 people as former concentration camp guards and said Monday it will have them placed on the immigration watch list of individuals to be barred from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Office of Special Investigations compiled the names with the assistance of a sophisticated new computer database. Names of suspected criminals and <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> persecutors are systematically checked against immigration records to determine if they are in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The names of individuals not found to be in this country are included in the watch list to prevent them from entering. <ORGANIZATION> OSI </ORGANIZATION> has listed thousands of such people in the past few years. But the 9,800 now to be placed on the watch list of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` for serving as concentration and death camp guards is probably the greatest number'' to be added at one time, said the office's chief, <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>. The watch list includes people who are prohibited from entering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> under a federal law barring individuals who assisted or otherwise participated in Nazi-sponsored persecution. The provision, known as the Holtzman Amendment, was invoked when Austrian President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was placed on the watch list last year following a decision by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORG