<TEXT>
 _ <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> relations with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are strained because of a perception the service tried to cover up problems with the B-1B bomber That is `` an absolutely false charge,'' <PERSON> Welch </PERSON> said, because in truth the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> itself `` was badly surprised by the lag in the development'' of B-1B radar-jamming gear. Nonetheless, `` we are -LRB- now -RRB- going to great pains to keep the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> thoroughly informed on anything that looks like a problem.'' _ There's no reason for concern at this point about a delay in flight testing the radar-evading Stealth, or B-2, bomber Sources have said the first flight test was pushed back four months to August because of technical problems. `` I think we've been very realistic about -LRB- the B-2 -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Welch </PERSON> said. `` Unlike some other programs, we did n't say five years in advance that we're going to fly that airplane on the 23rd of May. We knew better. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is asking for money to pay its pilots a salary bonus because re-enlistment rates have fallen to unacceptable levels Retention rates are running about 48 percent compared with the target 60 percent, and for the first time in years, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> expects to end fiscal 1989 with an overall shortage of pilots _ 22,312 on duty compared with 22,556 needed. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> also will try to keep its pilots happy by changing promotion policies to make it clear to young lieutenants and captains they should concentrate on flying, and not worry about finding staff jobs to make them more promotable _ And if he had his druthers, he would try to save money by closing unneeded bases