<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Gray Market,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court To Rule On Case Involving Trademarked Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday postponed until later in the year a ruling in a multibillion-dollar battle over so-called `` gray market'' goods, the growing business that allows consumers to purchase costly imports at steep discounts. The justices announced they again will hear arguments in the case in April with a decision expected by July. The case will be re-argued with Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who joined the court last month, taking part in the deliberations. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s participation in the case will give the court six members, a quorum, to consider the underlying dispute. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not take part as the court ruled, 5-3, on Monday that the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> does not have exclusive authority over the dispute. The majority said that a federal judge properly considered the case. The three justices who dissented did so on a procedural issue. They said the federal courts lacked jurisdiction, a decision that would in effect disqualify them from considering the merits of the case. The dispute is over interpretation of the Federal Tariff Act of 1930. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says the law allows gray market goods into the country without approval from trademark owners. Two leading discount distributors, <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> 47th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, also are defending the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORG