<HEAD>Briton Begins Begins Military Maneuvers In Falklands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> began a 25-day military exercise Monday to test its ability to protect the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> from invasion, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> said its forces would be on `` defensive alert.'' `` At this stage, it's very much a paper exercise,'' a ministry spokesman said. `` The exercise will start with intelligence reports that an enemy is raising the threat level. They will play out a scenario.'' An infantry batallion of 600-1 ,000 soldiers based in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> will fly to the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> archipelago March 17-18, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> claims the islands off its coast, which it calls the <LOCATION> Malvinas </LOCATION>, and invaded them in April 1982. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> sent a naval task force and won a 74-day war that killed 712 Argentines and 258 Britons. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> says the exercise, called Fire Focus, is purely defensive. One of its functions will be to test a new $ 690 million airport built since the war. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, the armed forces minister, said criticism of the exercise from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and other Latin American nations resulted from misunderstanding of its size. `` I do not see how something which is purely a defensive exercise can be seen as provocative,'' he said. `` We have to defend the Falklands. We had a very unfortunate experience six years ago. We not only have a right to have a defensive garrison in the Falklands, we have a responsibility to do so.'' The exercise, scheduled to end March 31, is the largest since the war and the first with reinforcements flown from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Military units could not be airlifted in 1982 because the airport was inadequate, and the naval force took weeks to reach the islands. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> says the islands are part of its inheritance from <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> colonial rule and claims <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> stole them in 1833. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has refused to discuss sovereignty, declaring that the 1,900 <ORGANIZATION> Falkland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> prefer to remain British, but <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said: `` In other respects we would like to have more normal relations with <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>.''
