ration. `` I feel considerable empathy and compassion for the students,'' <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON> said by telephone from her <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> office. `` I hope to speak with them soon, but given the intensity of this situation, it's only right for me to maintain some distance.'' Students had expressed outrage that <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON> does not speak sign language, but the incoming president vowed to accelerate immediately her study of the language. `` I have a facility for learning it, and now that I have been hired, I plan to have an intensive training program.'' <PERSON> Spilman </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON> was selected bu a 10-4 margin, with the three deaf members and one hearing member of the trustees' selection committee voting for one of the two deaf candidates <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bravin </PERSON>, a deaf trustee who headed the search committee, said he and the committee's other deaf members lobbied to no avail for a deaf president. `` Your expressions outline exactly what we put on the table,'' <PERSON> Bravin </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executive, told the students who remained on campus after <PERSON> Spilman </PERSON>'s announcement. `` We did the best we could do.'' <PERSON> Bravin </PERSON> asserted that the two other finalists for the post _ I. King <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Gallaudet </ORGANIZATION>'s dean of the college of arts and sciences, and <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Corson </PERSON>, superintendent of the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> for the Deaf, in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. _ both were qualified to be <ORGANIZATION> Gallaudet </ORGANIZATION>'s next president. `` No candidate has the perfect criteria, and they both were qualified. I think the committee's decision speaks for itself.''
