<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Monday cleared the way for the regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> telephone companies to offer certain new computerized information services, including voice storage and electronic mail. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, in a 66-page decision, refused to retreat from an earlier decision in which he said phone companies could transmit information but could not generate or manipulate the content of the information. `` It is the court's expectation that this easing of the information services restriction will avoid anticompetitive effects, and that it will at the same time bring this nation closer to the enjoyment of the full benefits of the information age,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said in his decision. Though <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>'s decision lifts the legal barrier to the Bell companies' offering of the new services, the companies still would need state and federal regulatory approval before they could integrate them into their networks. Industry experts and <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> company officials say the computer software for these services has been developed and could be offered to consumers in some parts of the country within one to two years. Voice storage and retrieval services would allow consumers to rely on the phone network for storing and retrieving messages, functions now performed by telephone answering machines. Electronic mail, a service now available in many private phone systems, allows the computer-to-computer transfer of messages. In addition, <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said the Bell companies can perform certain computerized `` gateway'' services such as data transmission, billing management and services that enable different computers to `` speak'' to each other. <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> said the decision was an important step toward making a wide range of information services available to American consumers. But both said the judge did not go far enough, and <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> said it will appeal the decision. `` We view this as a start, but only a start. We still are not allowed to provide content for information services,'' a <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> statement said. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolger </PERSON> said the company is `` particularly concerned'' that <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> is continuing to forbid the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies from electronic publishing of yellow page phone directories. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>'s September ruling allowed electronic white pages, but <PERSON> Bolger </PERSON> said the court's restrictions do not allow `` a sufficiently flexible and comprehensive'' electronic service for white pages directory. He also said <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>'s decision to continue to forbid the Bell companies from getting into the content side of information services will delay the delivery of more sophisticated services _ like home banking and shopping _ to most American consumers. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>, a telephone analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION>, said the decision was a `` major breakthrough'' for the regional phone companies. He said that in the long term, `` it will be a tremendous boon to the industry,'' though in the short-term will have little effect on the companies' earninings. `` Services like this, since they are software-based, should be high-profit services and voice storage and retrieval will create new -LRB- traffic -RRB- volumes for the phone networks,'' he said. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimmelman </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said the decision means regulation of the industry will become more important `` to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies from overpricing local phone service to finance these new services.'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, who oversees the antitrust decree that broke up the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> four years ago, has been reluctant to allow <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's offspring, the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies, to compete in areas where their control of the local phone networks would put them at an advantage over competitors. Last September, he refused to lift prohibitions on the Baby Bells that prevent them from making phone equipment or offering long-distance services. In considering the restrictions on information services, however, he opened the door slightly. Monday's ruling details the information-services options now open to the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies.
