governor's words constituted a crime?'' asked Craft. `` As I'm hearing them and reflecting on them,'' said <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON>, adding it took him `` about two seconds'' after hanging up the phone. Craft asked <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON> why he did not write down his conclusion that a crime had been committed. `` I did n't think it was necessary,'' said <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON>. `` Anyone with a legal background could read it and see this was an obstruction of an investigation.'' Craft kept <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON> on cross-examination for most of the day and said he would continue quizzing him Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic Minority Leader <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> told reporters the senators were growing restless and had requested that Craft be asked to conclude. `` It's difficult for us to listen to what many of us consider repetitious quetions,'' he said. `` If that's what they do in a court of law, I'm glad I'm not a lawyer.'' At one point, Craft asked if <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON> was surprised that his staff did n't tell him the governor had assigned a member of his Cabinet, <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, to investigate the death threat allegation. `` No, it did n't surprise me,'' said <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> is not a law enforcement officer. He's not competent to investigate it. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> works for him, and <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> would n't be taken seriously anywhere on earth that I know of.'' <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, was fired last week by acting Gov. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, who said he had publicly attacked government officials. <PERSON> Milstead </PERSON>, the trial's seventh 