 for allegedly padding her paycheck. Wheel was convicted on three counts of false swearing during a jury trial last month. She was accused of lying during an inquest into allegations that she submitted false pay vouchers. Wheel appeared in court briefly Monday. But she left after she and her attorneys were given one day to submit memoranda on why she should n't have to testify. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>, had said he and his client welcomed the misconduct hearing, calling it <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s opportunity to defend himself publicly. But most of the first day's testimony centered on Wheel and her activities as an assistant judge. In <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s written responses to the board's original charges, he said his relationship with Wheel was strictly professional and did not go beyond `` the amicable relationship expected of judges who work together.'' But the state on Monday attempted to depict a much closer relationship between the two. Court reporter <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Giard </PERSON> described a gathering she attended at the Holiday Inn in <LOCATION> Waterbury </LOCATION>. Wheel arrived with <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> on one arm and <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> on the other. `` She danced with Justice <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> that evening,'' <PERSON> Giard </PERSON> said. `` I remember looking over.'' Marks objected to much of the testimony about Wheel and her criminal case, but was overruled by <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Otterman </PERSON>, the chairman of the three-member hearing panel. The retirement of <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, 60, from the high court leaves few options for punishment if he is found guilty of judicial misconduct. He could be reprimanded or perhaps restricted from serving on the court under a law that allows retired justices to sit on certain cases.
