<HEAD>Defendant Waives Jury; Trial Begins In Case Of Bodies Found In
Apartment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unemployed handyman waived his right to a jury Monday and his trial began on charges of killing seven women and leaving their bodies to rot in and near his apartment. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> `` Marty'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s decision came as Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latrone </PERSON> prepared to begin jury selection. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> then entered pleas of innocent to seven counts each of murder, voluntary manslaughter and abuse of a corpse. The judge, after determining <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, 28, understood the charges, ordered the lawyers to begin presenting their cases. Both sides waived opening statements. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> moved for admission of all testimony and documents from a monthlong pretrial suppression hearing, including a confession <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> made to police, admitting strangling the seven women during sex. Latrone granted the request. During the pretrial hearing, defense attorney <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Moldovsky </PERSON>, contending his client is mentally incompetent, sought unsuccessfully to suppress the confession. <PERSON> Moldovsky </PERSON> argued the confession was made in violation of <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s constitutional rights and after <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> allegedly was beaten by police during 17 hours of interrogation. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> surrendered to police at his mother's urging Aug. 16 after a weeklong manhunt that started when he was evicted from his apartment because of a putrid stench. A police search uncovered the rotting bodies in <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s bedroom and leg and foot bones on the roof of his apartment house. In the confession, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> told police the bodies began piling up in his bedroom and he began having problems with maggots. He also told of his difficulty sleeping during the day because of birds on the roof outside his apartment, picking at human remains. <PERSON> Moldovsky </PERSON> has indicated that <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s defense will be insanity. The first witness called by the prosecution, acting Medical Examiner <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Catherman </PERSON>, said all seven deaths were homicides but said it was impossible in most cases to determine the cause of death because of decomposition.
