<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers in tanks and jeeps patrolled the main streets and poorer areas of the capital Monday to block further protests against the rising cost of living. President <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Balaguer </PERSON> summoned his advisers to discuss ways of controlling inflation, a major factor in recent unrest in this <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island nation of more than 6.5 million people. Protesters burned tires early Monday during a 24-hour strike in five low-income sectors of <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Domingo </LOCATION>. Three days of clashes last week between protesters and soldiers left one person dead and many businesses damaged. More than 300 people were arrested. The previous week, three people were killed and eight injured in protests in eight of the country's 26 provinces. Support seemed to be dwindling for a general strike called for Wednesday to demand lower prices for basic commodities, wage increases for public and private workers and better public services. `` We are willing to talk and hold sincere discussions with the authorities to solve the conflict as long as they manifest their sincere willingness to satisfy our demands,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Virtudes </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>. The group called for the general strike and organized earlier strikes in the last few weeks that shut down many parts of the capital. Labor groups opposed the strike, but promised to support it if it takes place. They want either a later strike or talks among the government, unions and business community to try to solve the economic problems. The main opposition party, the <ORGANIZATION> Dominican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, is also against the strike, alt