<HEAD>Serious Reading in Spain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lluis is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>ASSOCIATED PRESS WRITER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When publisher <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Herralde </PERSON> saw novels bearing his Anagrama Logo in all three bookstores on <LOCATION> Lanzarote </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, he knew things were looking up for serious books in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. `` Eight or nine years ago, it would have been impossible to find good novels and essays in bookstores in provincial towns, let alone on a small island in the Canaries,'' he said. `` It makes me optimistic about the future of Spanish publishing.'' <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Lluis </PERSON>, director of the year-old publishing company <ORGANIZATION> Circe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ediciones </ORGANIZATION>, agrees that now is the time for quality books in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. `` There's a new, discriminating reading public that wants more than the pulp best sellers,'' she said. `` They've read <PERSON> Marguerite </PERSON> <PERSON> Yourcenar </PERSON>, and they do n't want to settle for less.'' The increased interest in quality books in a country where newspaper readership is the lowest in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> comes more than a decade after the demise of Gen. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s dictatorship and his 36 years of cultural and intellectual repression. The change has been fairly sudden. It is due in part to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s 1986 entry into the European Common Market which has broadened many horizons <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Herralde </PERSON> also credited the newfound market to a decline in ideological topics and obscure experimental writing by some authors, and a return to the narrative _ both in Spanish and foreign literature. Those in the publishing industry, centered mainly in this northeastern port city, say Spaniards are now looking beyond their borders, learning foreign languages and reading good books. A 1985 study initiated by the Ministry of Culture on Spanish cultural behavior said that although 80 percent of <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> households possessed books, mainly encyclopedias or technical manuals, only 41 percent read any of them. The study also showed that the Spanish reading public is heavily concentrated in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION>, of which <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> is the capital _ the the most developed and educated regions of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The illiteracy rate is 7.4 percent in a population of 36.8 million, third highest in the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> after <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. Results also revealed that fewer than 11 percent of Spaniards ever set foot inside a library. `` Many people are still afraid to go inside bookstores or libraries because they think they're only for intellectuals,'' said <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ripoll </PERSON>, producer of `` Entrelineas'' -LRB- `` Between the Lines'' -RRB-, <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> state TV's new literary program. `` That's why so many of the books sold in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> are purchased at corner newsstands.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Herralde </PERSON> pointed out that the biggest single bookseller in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> _ with items ranging from how-to manuals to poetry collections _ is <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Corte </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingles </PERSON>, the country's only department store chain. Translations of foreign works _ primarily <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and English books _ make up about 70 percent of the lists of <LOCATION> Anagrama </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Circe </PERSON> and other quality houses. The other 30 percent is devoted to the works of established or new Spanish authors. Five years ago <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Herralde </PERSON>, a 52-year-old former industrial engineer, took a chance on <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Toole </PERSON>'s `` A Confederacy of Dunces,'' a cult novel published in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> when the unknown author's mother brought the manuscript to a publisher after his suicide. The book earned the author a posthumous Pulitzer Prize in 1981. The Spanish edition has gone into 22 printings and has sold 100,000 copies. The translation into Catalan, a language spoken by more than 5 million people in the northeastern part of the country, is due out in April. <PERSON> Pilar </PERSON> <PERSON> Raola </PERSON>, director of the Catalan publishing house Editorial Portic, said many Spanish-reading Catalans preferred to wait to read a translation of a foreign novel in their own language, resulting in a similar upsurge in Catalan-language publishing. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Spanish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION>, 38,814 titles were published in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1986 of which 7,483 were novels and essays. The average press run for a Spanish novel is between 3,500 and 4,000 copies. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Azua </PERSON>'s `` Diary of a Humiliated Man'' has gone into its third printing at <LOCATION> Anagrama </LOCATION> in three months following its publication in December after winning the firm's coveted Herralde literary award. Chilean author <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>'s `` <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Luna </PERSON>'' and `` Belle du Seigneur'' by French author <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> have been jockeying for first place on the best-seller list of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s leading newspaper <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pais </ORGANIZATION> for the past six months. Five of the 10 top-selling books on the list are by Spanish authors. The most successful Spanish novel this century is <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Gironella </PERSON>'s `` Cypresses Believe in God,'' set in the years leading up to the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War. Since its publication in the late 1950s, the book has sold over 4 million copies. The burst of interest in quality fiction has led <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> publishing giants to set up smaller collections devoted to serious fiction and essays, <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Herralde </PERSON> said. And the nationwide Readers' Circle book club began including quality foreign and domestic fiction several years ago at the request of its 1.3 million members, according to spokesman <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentz </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
