<FIRST>a i PM-LifeAbroad-France Adv11   03-07 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Life Abroad-France, Adv 11,0701</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs March 11 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: France _ A Tax-Free `Pousse Cafe'?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondents on the way of life in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON> is n't given much chance in his candidacy for the office of president, but he's getting some attention with his idea to restore an orchard owner's benefit dating back to the French Revolution. In 1791, owners of orchards were granted the right to distill tax-free each year 2.6 gallons of eau de vie, the alcoholic beverage that is sipped after meals and called `` pousse cafe'' or `` digestif.'' The distillers would pay no tax so long as they did n't offer it for sale. The license to distill was passed on from one generation to another until 1961 when a new law canceled the right to inherit the license. Eau de vie comes in various forms, depending on the region. In <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION>, for example, it is made from apples and is called calvados. In <LOCATION> Alsace </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, pears and plums are used; in the <LOCATION> Auvergne </LOCATION> region of central <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> it is made from hazelnuts. `` When my mother died six months ago, I inherited her orchard,'' said <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON>, `` but the license died with her and so I can no longer make eau de vie without paying tax.'' <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON>'s bucolic campaign headquarters is his 60-acre sheep farm in the village of <LOCATION> Chezeaux </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Haut-Marne </LOCATION> department of eastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. His name does not figure in the opinion polls, he has no political party machine behind him, or image advisers cultivating a presidential package for the balloting April 24 and runoff May 8. But he has been getting his message out and has already received letters of support from 500 mayors, the minimum necessary to declare his candidacy formally. `` Our method of raising support is by word of mouth,'' <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. But he thinks it unlikely that he will become <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s successor in the presidency. He is simply using the elections, he said, to defend what he sees as an honorable rural tradition. Others, however, compare the lot of French eau de vie distillers to the tale of Tristan and <PERSON> Isolde </PERSON>, or the myth of the eternal return, because the argument to restore the inherited licenses resurfaces from time to time. In a country that has one of the highest rates of alcoholism in the world, the abolition of the right to distill tax-free eau de vie might seem like a good thing. But <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON> disagrees. He wants to clean up the image of the `` bouilleurs de cru,'' as eau de vie makers are known. `` We want people to realize that we are not just purveyors of alcoholism,'' he said. <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON> maintains that the major distilleries are more to blame for the problem of alcoholism than farmers who make a couple of gallons out of plums or apples. According to <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON>, 2.11 million gallons of alcohol were drunk in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> last year, of which just 15,840 gallons were homemade eau de vie. `` This shows how ridiculous the argument is,'' he said. `` We make less than 1 percent of the total consumption in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.'' Gobinot emphasizes that traditional rural skills, and therefore jobs, are disappearing as a result of the 1961 law. Only a handful of craftsmen making wooden barrels remain and the fruit trees are no longer pruned as they used to be, he said. The distiller with his `` alambic ambulant'' -LRB- mobile still -RRB-, going from village to village in <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> to turn apples into calvados, was once a familiar figure. `` The farmer who picks his own fruit is proud to distill his own eau de vie,'' <PERSON> Gobinot </PERSON> said. `` He does everything himself and is making a natural product. `` I drink very little myself. But I take great pleasure in offering a glass of friendship when people come to my house.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs March 11</NOTE>
