<HEAD>A Community `Tender Care Corps' Keeps Watch on Newborn</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Infants, b0123</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAMATO VILLAGE, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the reasons given for so many healthy babies in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is the <ORGANIZATION> Tender </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of volunteer women who visit new mothers and their babies in their own homes. The corps operates on the tradition that neighbors look out for each other. It mobilizes 80,000 mothers who volunteer to keep tabs on the health of 2 million households with children in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s outlying cities and hamlets Here in <LOCATION> Yamato </LOCATION> village, a collection of small farms and quarries perched among mountaintop forests, volunteer <PERSON> Hatsuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirayama </PERSON> visits six families every month. She makes her rounds on foot over steep paths and concrete-paved roads 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` Our purpose is to see that healthy babies are born,'' explained Mrs. <PERSON> Hirayama </PERSON>, a woman in her fifties with children of her own. `` The public health nurse ca n't always visit homes, so I do.'' One of the mothers she visits is <PERSON> Yoshimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirayama </PERSON>, a distant relative in this town of 1,890 people. The visits began when the 24-year-old housewife became pregnant with her second child, which turned out to be a daughter, <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON>, who now is now 10 months old. `` She told me to breast feed,'' <PERSON> Yoshimi </PERSON> said. `` She told me to eat things that would build bones _ small fish, lots of milk. `` She's like another mother. When I had my first baby I did n't know anybody here, but I could go to Mrs. <PERSON> Hirayama </PERSON> and ask her anything. <PERSON> Yoshimi </PERSON>'s pregnancy was normal. She followed her doctor's instructions to undergo health checks every three weeks during the first two trimesters, then biweekly and weekly until delivery In between came prenatal care and childbirth classes at the village hall. In April, after she gave birth to <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON>, a public health nurse stopped by to check on the mother and baby after their return from the hospital. Mrs. <PERSON> Hirayama </PERSON> took it from there. `` Any teeth?'' she asked on a recent visit, pulling down <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON>'s lower lip. `` Are you hiding them?'' Her notes on <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON>'s diet, bedtimes and skin color are turned over to the health nurse, who evaluates them and recommends doctor's visits or looks in on the baby herself, if necessary. Mrs. <PERSON> Hirayama </PERSON> fills in monthly visit cards for each child she sees on her rounds until the child turns 6. Then it is time for school teachers to keep an eye out.
</TEXT>
