<HEAD>NEW YORK: the other.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>' job does n't end when the curtain goes up. During the performance, she's in the dressing room or the wings, ready to do minor touch-ups. As for <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, the makeup is with him for 12 hours on Wednesdays and Saturdays, when he performs twice; seven hours on the four days when he does just one show. At the end of the show, <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> applies vast amounts of mineral oil to remove the makeup, which is peeled off gently so as not to irritate the skin. `` There are n't many makeup jobs in theater because nowadays actors learn to do their own makeup,'' says <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, who grew up in <LOCATION> Surrey </LOCATION> and moved to <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> before going to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to study at Complexions, the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Makeup </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> met <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, the makeup designer, when he spoke at the school. He hired her to work on `` Phantom.'' It was her first job. `` It was quite an extensive training period he put her through,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> says. `` I remember him throwing all her brushes from college out the door and saying ` What's this, girl? You ca n't use this, girl. It was something out of <PERSON> Dickens </PERSON>, and I had to sit there absolutely quiet. But it worked.'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> adapted quickly to her on-the-job training. `` We had done a lot of this in theory at school, but in practice I had never done it although I always wanted to get into prosthetic makeup,'' she says. The makeup design for `` Phantom'' was first discussed during the summer of 1986, several months before the show opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at Her Majesty's Theater. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, scenic designer <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjornson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> experimented with many different kinds of makeup. They found they were limited by practical considerations. `` There were restrictions _ not being able to cover the nose because of breathing or going inside the mouth too far because of the singing or covering the ears because it would interfere with listening to the music,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> says. What the three of them came up with is what <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> tries to recapture at every performance. `` It's interesting. People say ` How can you do the same show every day when you're an actor?''' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> says. `` It's exactly the same thing with the makeup. It's like painting. Every day is a challenge to paint that picture.''
