<HEAD>India Building Navy in its `Zone of Peace'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation that wants to turn the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> into a `` zone of peace'' has just acquired a nuclear submarine to add to its two aircraft carriers and 110 other naval vessels. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s acquisition last month of the nuclear submarine from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is part of a naval expansion since failing in its efforts of almost 20 years to clear the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> of big-power navies. The expansion has aroused criticism from neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has warships in the ocean along with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Within the past two years, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> also has acquired five conventional submarines, its second aircraft carrier and at least five Indian-built navy ships. It has plans to buy more _ including possibly other <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear subs _ and to build warships ranging from submarines to another aircraft carrier for its fleet. `` It's the full range of naval warfare. They're building a first-class navy,'' a Western naval analyst said. When the 47,000-member Indian navy got the carrier <ORGANIZATION> Hermes </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> last year and renamed it Viraat -LRB- Imposing -RRB-, the chief of naval staff at the time, Adm. <PERSON> R.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tahiliani </PERSON>, said: `` We finally have a round-the-clock blue -LRB- deep -RRB- water navy.'' While greater naval strength seems to belie <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s pleas before the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> for a zone of peace in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, it matches the country's growing might. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> also has a 1-million-man army, the world's fourth largest, and is acquiring modern weapons. Each step up, however, is ascribed to the need to match the growing arsenals of others, chiefly neighboring rivals <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but also the Western powers. `` The strategies of outside powers in our region have forced upon us expenditure in building military strength which we would much rather have deployed for the removal of poverty,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said as the nuclear sub Chakra was commissioned. `` The <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> has been militarized and infested with nuclear weapons flouting the overwhelming sentiment within the region in favor of establishing a zone of peace.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> first proposed a zone of peace for the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> in the early 1970s, and the Non-Aligned Movement -LRB- Third World -RRB- endorsed the concept. The proposal then went to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, which in 1971 adopted a declaration calling for a peace zone and urging the dismantling of big powers' air and naval bases in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. But a planned <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> conference on the issue has never been held, although a committee has been meeting in hopes of bringing one about by 1990. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has endorsed the idea, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s naval buildup initially was attributed to the development of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base in the early 1980s at <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, an island in the <LOCATION> Chagos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Archipelago </LOCATION> about 1,000 miles southwest of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. An Indian naval expert, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he did not believe his nation faces a real threat from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or other Western ships protecting oil shipping in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, but he added: `` If you have troubled waters close to home, you think about what you might have to do.'' He said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> believed more sea power was needed to protect its 4,937 miles of coastline and to keep a competitive edge in naval technology. Of the newly acquired nuclear sub, he said: `` It's a system without which a navy is not viable. It takes the game to a new step altogether.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has condemned the acquisition of the sub as an escalation of the military buildup in the region. Press reports say <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, with no nuclear submarine, is pressing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for P-3 anti-submarine aircraft. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> has said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s acquisition of a nuclear sub `` clearly introduces a new weapons technology into the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> region. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is opposed to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> having a nuclear submarine because of a lack of safeguards, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> added. Neither <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> nor <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has signed the nuclear non-proliferation treaty. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> exploded a nuclear device in 1974, and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is thought to be on the verge of developing nuclear weapons. Both nations say their nuclear plans are peaceful in design. The new Chakra submarine, for the moment leased by the Soviets to the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> navy, is not believed to carry nuclear weapons. The Western naval analyst, who insisted his name not be used, said the Charlie I class sub is `` 1960s technology. It's an old boat.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s second aircraft carrier, the Viraat, was originally commissioned in 1959, and the Western expert noted that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> `` does not have enough planes for one carrier, let alone two.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, however, is buying <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harrier </LOCATION> aircraft and Sea King commando helicopters for its carriers. It also has bought three late-1970s vintage Kilo class Soviet submarines and two West German HDW 209s, called `` search and kill subs,'' to update its fleet of eight Soviet-made Foxtrot subs. In addition, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is upgrading its three shipyards to build warships and constructing its largest naval base near <LOCATION> Karwar </LOCATION>, 285 miles south of <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION> on the west coast. There are reports the navy is expanding an existing base on its far-flung <LOCATION> Nicobar </LOCATION> islands, 1,035 miles from the country's southern tip but only about 100 miles from <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. The Indian naval expert saw these developments in light of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s need to protect itself. `` You need military power for your own security, not that you have expansionist ambitions,'' he said. His Western counterpart said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s rationale for an expanding navy was its view of itself as the regional power of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Indian navy men also see themselves as heirs to British sea power from the days when <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> controlled the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> to protects its trade routes to <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the Western analyst said. `` They want a navy they can operate throughout the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` The Brits were there before. They want to be there too.''
