<HEAD>Japanese Favor Accepting Foreign Workers in Certain Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The majority of Japanese responding to an opinion poll favored accepting temporary foreign workers into <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> if their skills and effciency are needed, the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. An agency official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 11.0 percent of those responding thought <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should allow temporary foreign laborers, such as construction workers, waiters, maids and waitresses, to find work in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> without any conditions. He said 63 percent said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should accept foreign workers under certain conditions. Only 4.8 percent opposed <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s acceptance of any foreign workers at all, the official said The agency questioned 3,000 people aged 20 or over and 1,000 firms throughout the nation at random last October. Among Japanese firms that had employed foreign workers, 62.7 percent of those responding said they would employ them in the future, while 3.1 percent said they would not employ them any more. The others said they did not know. Of the Japanese firms that never had employed foreign workers, 21.9 percent of those responding said they would employ them in the future and 29.9 percent said they would not. In general, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> now limits foreigners working here to scholars, language teachers, technicians and performing artists, including musicians and dancers. But an increasig number of foreigners have been working illegally in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where wages paid in the strong yen currency make jobs more attractive. Last year, the number of foreigners who violated <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s immigration laws _ mostly by working illegally _ rose by 33.6 percent from a year earlier to a record 14,129, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Monday A ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 11,307 people were caught overstaying their visas and working illegally. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> asked employers in late January not to hire any foreigners who have only tourist visas.
