<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-Merger     03-07 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Merger,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court To Hear Merger Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to hear a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to take a bigger tax bite out of some corporate mergers. The court said it will review a ruling stemming from the acquisition of a small <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> company by a corporation traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The smaller company, <ORGANIZATION> Basin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surveys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was owned by <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Buckhannon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION> It provides services to the petroleum industry. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> sold the business in 1979 to N.L. Industries of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which produces petroleum equipment, chemicals and metals. N.L. Industries gave <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> 300,000 shares of its stock and $ 3.25 million to acquire Basin Surveys. At issue in the case was whether the cash payment, commonly called `` boot,'' should be taxed as a capital gain or considered a dividend and taxed as ordinary income. Generally, the capital gain tax rate is lower. The tax reform bill enacted in 1986 eliminated the different tax rates for capital gains and ordinary income. But the administration said the different treatment will still apply to some corporate shareholders. Also, in urging the court to consider the government appeal, <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sometime in the future might restore for all taxpayers the different treatment of ordinary income and capital gains. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in favor of <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> last September, sparing him from paying $ 972,505 in taxes. The appeals court said, `` We regard the boot as a cash payment by N.L. in return for <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s relinquishment of a portion of his interest in the newly reorganized corporation. Because <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> surrendered more than 20 percent of his interest in N.L., he is entitled to capital gain treatment.'' The appeals court arrived at the 20 percent figure by noting that N.L. Industries offere <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> two choices in the merger: he could receive either 425,000 shares of N.L. stock or 300,000 shares plus $ 3.25 million in cash. The appeals court said <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, by choosing the latter option, in effect gave up more than 20 percent of his interest in <LOCATION> N.L </LOCATION>. Industries in return for the cash. The appeals court said that under federal law a shareholder who relinquishes more than 20 percent of his corporate control and is less than a 50 percent shareholder after the transaction is entitled to have cash proceeds from the transaction treated as capital gains. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the ruling is in conflict with decisions by other federal appeals courts. They said the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> should eliminate the confusion. The case is Commissioner of Internal Revenue vs. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, 87-1168.
</TEXT>
