 <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, wounded from possibly uncollectable Third World loans, is seeking to sell its profitable consumer finance unit to raise capital, the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. Quoting banking sources it did not identify, the newspaper said the nation's sixth-largest banking concern is asking between $ 500 million and $ 600 million for <LOCATION> Huntingdon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pa.-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has about $ 3 billion in assets. The banking company has been forced to take austerity measures because of a $ 1.14 billion loss last year, due mainly to a $ 1.7 billion addition to reserves that reflected the questionable collectability of some Third World loans, a problem afflicting many American banks. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>, a Manufacturers Hanover spokesman in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he could not comment on the Journal report. But he said the bank has consistently stated it would rebuild capital partly via property sales and expense cuts. `` We've said all along there is a host of assets we can realize gains on,'' <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> said. `` It is part of our game plan to get shareholder equity replenished.'' Banking industry analysts have said Manufacturers Hanover's consumer finance business is considered highly prized and profitable within the company, so a sale would reflect on the seriousness of the bank's capital needs On the other hand, the consumer finance unit is a stand-alone operation, so it could be sold much more easily that other company property.
