<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-Taxes     03-07 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Taxes,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Tax Break From Stock Losses, Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Businesses that lose money from the sale of stock are n't entitled to special tax breaks no matter why the stock was purchased, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decided today. The court, voting 8-0, ruled against an <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> conglomerate that sought to claim as an ordinary-loss deduction for federal tax purposes a $ 10 million loss from the sale of stock in a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> bank it once controlled. <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> in 1969 had acquired more than 65 percent of the stock of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, the fourth largest bank in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed a law in 1970 that prohibited conglomerates that owned a bank from expanding their non-bank business through new acquisitions in other industries. <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION>, which owns trucking, furniture manufacturing, data processing and other businesses, decided to divest itself of the bank stock. The 1970 law gave it 10 years to sell the bank stock. Because of public awareness that <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> was under legal obligation to divest itself, disposing of the bank stock without taking a big loss was difficult. At the same time, the bank's finances were deteriorating. <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> therefore acquired additional stock in the bank in an attempt to keep it solvent. The conglomerate began selling off the bank stock in 1975, and sought to claim the losses as ordinary losses rather than capital losses _ a tax advantage. The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the losses suffered by <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> were capital losses. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> rejected <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION>'s arguments that the stock was not bought for typical investment purposes but for business purposes _ and therefore its sale should yield ordinary losses The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> but other federal appeals courts had reached conflicting conclusions. Writing for the high court today, Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said motivation behind the stock purchase is irrelevant `` to the question whether the asset is property held by a taxpayer ... and is thus within -LRB- federal tax law's -RRB- general definition of capital asset.'' `` Because the capital stock held by -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- falls within the broad definition of the term ` capital asset' in -LRB- the tax code -RRB- and is outside the classes of property excluded from capital-asset status, the loss arising from the sale of the stock is a capital loss,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not participate in the decision. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> vs. Commissioner of Internal Revenue, 86-751.
</TEXT>
