<FIRST>u f PM-Bonds     03-07 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bonds,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices and interest rates stabilized in quiet early trading today following Friday's sell-off. `` The market seems to be on dead center right now,'' said <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> B. Front, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Stein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Farnham </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investment and mutual-fund management firm. `` There does n't seem to be any news affecting the market.'' By midday, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond was up about 1-32 point while its yield, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to 8.46 percent from 8.47 percent late Friday. The bellwether issue had plunged about two points, or $ 20 per $ 1,000 in face amount, on Friday, after the government reported unexpectedly high February employment levels, raising doubts about forecasts of an economic slowdown later this year. The government said the economy created half a million jobs last month, dropping the civilian unemployment rate to 5.7 percent, its lowest since 1979. The January rate had been 5.8 percent. Front said the market was currently involved in a `` tug of war'' of sorts on the outlook for interest rates. `` The bulls point to lower commodity prices _ the price of gold continues to fall, oil prices continue to slip _ and other signs of weakness in economic activity,'' he said. `` The bears look at the employment numbers ... which were shockingly good and say ... the economy is likely to accelerate. `` I think a lot of people are going back to their drawing boards.'' Interest rates have fallen sharply since fears of recession surfaced after the stock market crash five months ago. But bondholders worry that with some signs of economic growth, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> may want to tighten its credit policies, thus pushing interest rates higher, to prevent inflation from heating up. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds today, prices of short-term governments were unchanged, intermediate maturities rose 1-32 point and 20-year issues were off 1-32 point, according to figures provided by <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Index </ORGANIZATION>, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.01 to 113.3. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, lost 0.04 to 1,183.34. In corporate trading, industrials and utilities were unchanged in light trading, according to the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, was off 0.06 to 284.36 Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills were up 2 basis points to 5.72 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. Six-month bills - fell 1 basis point to 5.94 percent and one-year bills were unchanged at 6.27 percent The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 6 9-16 percent, up from 6 -LCB- percent late Friday.
