<HEAD>Third Qtr Earnings Up 22 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leading foodmaker H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 22 percent surge in third-quarter earnings Monday, attributing the improvement to higher sales volume, acquisitions and the beneficial effects of a cheaper dollar. The company said earnings for the three months ended Jan. 27 totaled $ 91 million or 69 cents a share, compared with $ 74.7 million or 55 cents a share in the year-earlier period. Sales totaled $ 1.25 billion vs. $ 1.08 billion, a 15 percent rise. `` We are encouraged by the earnings record achieved to date through our existing business base as well as the superior market opportunities offered by our strategic world-wide acquisitions,'' said Chairman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J.F </PERSON>. <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON>. `` We are optimistic that we will again achieve fiscal year results consisted with our historical trends.'' The Pittsburgh-based company embarked on a series of acquisitions last year, notably in the pet-food business, in which it bought <LOCATION> Mavar </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>, two American concerns. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> also recently acquired <ORGANIZATION> Orlando </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, an important Spanish food company. The dollar's depreciation also helped <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> because its U.S.-produced foods became more competitive overseas. At the same time, profits from goods produced and sold by <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>'s foreign operations rose when converted into dollars. For the nine-months ended Jan. 27, <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said it earned $ 284.3 million or $ 2.14 a share, a 16.3 percent gain over the $ 244.4 million or $ 1.78 a share in the year-earlier period. Sales rose 13 percent from $ 3.3 billion to $ 3.8 billion.
