<HEAD>Cheap New World: Europeans Rediscovering America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spurred by the low dollar and cheaper air fares, Europeans from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION> are rediscovering <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at a record pace. Tourist visa applications are flooding <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulates across <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and tour operators say the number of bookings to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is up sharply from last year's record. `` The numbers -LRB- of visa applicants -RRB- are increasing dramatically,'' said <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, chief of the non-immigrant visa branch at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Mudd </PERSON>, chief of consular services at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulate </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, said the consulate issued about 600,000 tourist visas last year. `` We expect a 30 percent to 50 percent rise this year, and this pretty much reflects the rest of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mudd </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The Association of <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which includes 21 major airline companies, said the total number of Europeans flying to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has increased about 48 percent since 1985. According to the most recent statistics available to the Brussels-based association, 7.2 million Europeans took flights to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from January to October 1987. Officials across <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> polled by the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> said the first two months of this year indicate that 1988 will be a boom year for travel to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> provide the bulk of tourists visiting the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the two countries are expected to combine for nearly 2 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trips this year. <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said the number of non-immigrant visas issued in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was expected to reach 900,000 this year from 642,000 in 1987. January saw a 69 percent increase in non-immigant visas over January 1987, and February figures rose 66 percent over the same month last year, <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Beecham </PERSON>, owner of American Round-up, a travel agency in <LOCATION> Hemel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hempstead </LOCATION>, 25 miles north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said her business was flourishing. `` The growth in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> travel because of the dollar recently is tremendous. In the last three months I've had the same amount of business as all last year,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Beecham </PERSON>, whose agency specializes in adventure vacations to the Western states. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where the dollar has dropped 50 percent in three years, travel agencies also are thriving as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tours become cheaper. `` Our January figures are 25 percent over last January's when we had 25,705 bookings,'' said <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielander </PERSON> of Deutsches Reisebuero, a travel agency. His agency offers two-week trips to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for $ 1,000 dollars, only $ 350 more than a two-week stay at a <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> resort. The Swiss are also frequent international travelers: 235,000 of them visited the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year, a 27 percent increase over 1986. A further rise is expected this year. In <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> official in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> said bookings for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destinations were up 30 percent this year compared with 1987. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Pantelides </PERSON>, manager of <ORGANIZATION> Manos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s largest travel agency, said the dollar's drop was a windfall for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trips `` America is much better value for money compared to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' In <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillen </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, said there has been a 12 percent increase in the past five months in tourist visa applications for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, compared with the same period in 1987. In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials reported a 60 percent to 70 percent rise in the number of visa applications, and in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> they said it was up 38 percent in the last five months.
