<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Europe, Gold Varies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar fell against most major currencies in European trading Monday. Gold prices were mixed. Foreign exchange dealers said the British pound gained almost 4 cents against the dollar _ a remarkable one-day advance _ and also rose against every other currency. Reports in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that British interest rates would stay high and that the economy was growing at a strong pace were credited for the pound's strength. Sterling's rise quickened when it became clear the state-run Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> was not selling pounds to prevent sterling from rising against the West German mark. A higher exchange rate means British goods become more expensive abroad. The bank's refusal to act was in line with government policy to encourage companies to be more competitive by becoming more efficient. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.8135 late Monday, up from $ 1.7740 late Friday. Other late rates for the dollar late Monday, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.6765 West German marks, down from 1.6940; 1.3870 Swiss francs, down from 1.4030; 5.6880 French francs, down from 5.7300; 1.8840 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9010; 1.239.75 Italian lire, down from 1,248.00; and 1.2562 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2547. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> earlier, the dollar closed at 128.87 Japanese yen, down from 129.22 late Friday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Monday, the dollar traded at 128.30 Gold prices were mixed. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major trading center, gold closed at a late bid price of $ 437.20 a troy ounce, down from $ 437.50 late Friday. The late bid price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was $ 436, up from $ 432 late Friday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 438.75, up from $ 438.21. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 6.42 a troy ounce, up from $ 6.41.
