<HEAD>Strong Second-Quarter Growth in Hiring Predicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A significant number of American companies will bolster hiring this spring, a leading temporary job service said Monday in an unusually optimistic quarterly forecast on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employment. <ORGANIZATION> Manpower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its Employment Outlook Survey indicated 29 percent of respondents plan to raise employment rolls in the April-June quarter, while 6 percent expect declines. Sixty-two percent plan no change and 3 percent do n't know, the survey stated. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fromstein </PERSON>, Manpower president, said it was the strongest spring hiring forecast in four years and suggested manufacturers in all regions of the country are unusually buoyant about the economy. Makers of large durable goods are among the most optimistic of all employers, with 32 percent planning payroll increases and 7 percent planning cutbacks, the survey showed. Among construction companies, 36 percent anticipate payroll increases and 7 percent anticipate cutbacks. Among retailers, 31 percent plan increased payrolls and 6 percent plan decreases. Even in the financial services industry, which was particularly affected by the October collapse in stock prices, the spring hiring forecast was still optimistic. Twenty-three percent of respondents plan to add employees and 7 percent will cut back. Manpower has issued the quarterly survey for the past 12 years and calls it as a significant indicator of employment trends. Conducted in last two weeks of February, the survey was based on telephone interviews with more than 13,000 public and private employers in 401 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities. The margin of error is 5 percent, the company said. Based in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, Manpower describes itself as the world's largest temporary service firm, annually providing jobs to more than 700,000 people through 1,350 offices in 33 countries
