<HEAD>Livestock Futures Soar As Market Looks Forward To Greater Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Livestock and meat futures prices rose sharply Monday as traders looked beyond the cash market's current problems and saw meat sales improving in the months ahead. On other markets, energy futures slid lower; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; precious metals retreated; and stock-index futures advanced. Slack retail demand for meat during Lent led to a slowdown in slaughters last week, prompting fears of a growing supply of slaughter-ready cattle and hogs. Analysts said those fears, along with the closing of at least one major beef packing plant, were largely responsible for losses on livestock futures last week at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. But indications of a cattle buildup did not surface Monday, leading many traders to rethink their positions and look ahead to a resurgence in demand after Easter, analysts said. `` Prices went down last week on ideas we were backing up cattle -LRB- but -RRB- we have n't seen any proof of that yet,'' said <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Lind-Waldock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thomson-McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said traders had turned their attention to the future and away from the industry's current woes. `` They're thinking that retail demand will pick up, packers will have to accumulate supplies and the cattle feeders will reap the profits by being able to sell cattle at higher prices,'' <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said some traders also bought livestock futures on ideas that prices for future delivery of cattle and hogs had fallen more sharply than conditions warranted. And some were betting that a winter storm moving into the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> would disrupt the movement of animals to market, resulting in temporarily tight supplies and higher prices, <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said. The bullish enthusiasm for cattle futures overflowed into the pork pits, analysts said. Live cattle settled .87 cent to 1.38 cents higher with the contract for delivery in April at 71.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .80 cent to 1.10 cents higher with March at 80.35 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent to 1.25 cents higher with April at 43.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.20 cents to 1.85 cents higher with March at 54.70 cents a pound. Energy futures prices retreated in moderate trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following a slight advance in the previous session. Analysts attributed the decline to speculation that some member nations of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries were selling oil at a discount. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 22 cents lower with April at $ 15.37 a barrel; heating oil was .13 cent to .25 cent lower with April at 43.41 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .34 cent to .57 cent lower with April at 43.94 cents a gallon. Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, although soybean futures were mixed. Expectations of new export business supported the markets. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced after the close that it had sold 1.6 million bushels of wheat Friday in the last of last week's three auctions for surplus, government-owned wheat The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> had targeted 10 million bushels for sale at that auction. The agency also announced it would hold three auctions a week, each with a 10-million-bushel target, through March 25. Wheat settled -RCB- cent to 2 cents higher with March at $ 3.04 a bushel; corn was 1 -LCB- cents to 2 -RCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.00 -RCB- a bushel; oats were \ cent to 4 cents higher with March at $ 1.90 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 1 \ cent lower to 2 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 6.13 -RCB- a bushel Gold and silver futures retreated slightly on the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But despite its weak tone, the market appeared to have shaken off the recessionary expectactions that had weighed on prices in recent weeks, said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled 10 cents to 30 cents lower with April at $ 438.60 a troy ounce; silver was 3.2 cents to 3.5 cents lower with March at $ 6.395 a troy ounce Stock-index futures advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 1.10 points higher at 268.30. The underlying spot index closed nearly unchanged at 267.38.
