<HEAD>London Stock Exchange Chief To Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sir <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodison </PERSON> said Monday he is resigning at the end of the year as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which he piloted through its `` Big Bang'' computer revolution in 1986 and the market crash last October. <PERSON> Goodison </PERSON>, 53, will take over the chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Trustee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> next Jan. 1. `` I have served on the <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> council </ORGANIZATION> for the past 20 years and been chairman for the past 12. I have been chairman during a period of great innovation and change and now feel that the structure for the future has been built,'' <PERSON> Goodison </PERSON> said in a statement. An election among the stock exchange's members for a new chairman is likely in the fall. <PERSON> Goodison </PERSON> in his new post succeeds Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Read </PERSON>, who will be 70 on March 29 and due for retirement this year from leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Trustee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which is a financial services group as well as a bank with 1.9 million investors. <PERSON> Goodison </PERSON> has been chairman of stockbrokers <ORGANIZATION> Quilter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goodison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> since 1975 He said the stock crash of last October and November had nothing to do with his move, and that the old-style exchange could not have absorbed the wave of selling. When he became chairman, <PERSON> Goodison </PERSON> was confronted with the then <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> government's decision to reconstruct the stock exchange by separating market-makers and brokers into different partnerships. Eleven years later came the Big Bang, on Oct. 27, 1986, ending fixed commissions and the distinction between brokers who were agents in the buying and selling of shares and stock-jobbers who actively traded in shares at prices they quoted to brokers.
