<HEAD>Lorimar Discussing Business Combination with Warner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to show f0257 is a writethru.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Loss-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar-Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which was formed two years ago by a merger but has seen its aggressive expansion plans disintegrate, said Monday it is discussing the possibility of being acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Word of the negotiations helped push <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price up $ 2.50 a share to $ 15 In the past year, the stock has traded as high as $ 25.25 and as low as $ 6.62 -LCB-. `` I'd say the odds -LRB- of a takeover -RRB- are 50-50,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, an entertainment industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He estimated the final price of a deal would be `` somewhere between $ 14 and the high teens.'' <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> has about 45.9 million shares outstanding. In a brief statement, <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>, a leading supplier of original television programming, said it was approached by New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and preliminary talks were under way `` to explore the desirability of a business combination.'' However, <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> said its board has made no decision as to whether such a deal would be in the best interests of shareholders. The company also noted it has been approached about possible mergers in the past and nothing came of those overtures. The Culver City-based company was formed in February 1986 by the stock-swap combination of <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, best known as the producer of such long-running television series as `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>'' and `` Knots Landing,'' and New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which got most of its revenue from animated shows such as `` Thundercats'' and such programs as `` Peoples Court'' and `` Love Connection.'' For the 1987-88 television season, the company is producing 12 hours of prime time and 16 -LCB- hours of syndicated shows, including `` The Days and Nights of <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>,'' `` Mama's Family,'' `` It's a Living'' and `` She's the Sheriff.'' For the first nine months of of its current fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> posted a loss of $ 82.6 million on revenues of $ 616.8 million. The deficit included $ 45 million in writedowns on five movies and $ 22 million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video unit. Management of both its movie and home-video units was recently ousted. For fiscal 1987 ended last March 31, the company lost $ 58.6 million, mostly because of restructuring costs, on revenues of $ 766.2 million. In recent years, <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> sought to expand far beyond its successful roots as a producer of television shows. It bought advertising agencies, sought to build a network of television stations and acquired a children's publishing unit, but it has shed most of those operations in a back-to-basics restructuring announced last June. The company has just completed the sale of the ad agencies _ <PERSON> Bozell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Kenyon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Eckhardt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Poppe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tyson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ to members of their management for about $ 100 million, posting a pre-tax profit of $ 16 million. In late 1986, <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> had agreed to buy seven big-city <PERSON> Storer </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Wometco </ORGANIZATION> television stations from <LOCATION> Kohlberg </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> for $ 1.85 billion. The move would have given <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> 12 stations around the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. However, the deal with <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> collapsed as the bottom fell out of the market for television stations, and the company has sold some of the stations it already owned and is seeking buyers for the remainder. The company also sold its children's publishing unit. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> is the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> studio, is a leading record producer and is a major cable television operator. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s financial results have been strong. In 1987, its profit rose 77 percent to $ 328.1 million, or $ 2.09 a share, from $ 185.8 million, of $ 1.26 a share, the previous year. The 1987 figures included a net gain of $ 37.3 million on the sale of investments while the 1986 results included a gain of $ 48.4 million from the sale of investments and a gain from discontinued operations. Revenue for 1987 rose 20 percent to $ 3.4 billion from $ 2.84 billion. Its <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> film unit had the best year in its history, with an operating profit of $ 176.4 million, compared to $ 172.2 million in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s music operation posted a 1987 operating profit of $ 213.9 million, up from $ 150.6 million, and operating profit from the cable and broadcasting division jumped to $ 46.1 million for the year from $ 16.2 million in 1986.
