<HEAD>A.H. Robins Reports Net Loss Despite Record Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although sales for the <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> jumped 11 percent for the final three months of 1987, the pharmaceutical company reported a net loss of $ 1.69 billion for the period because of costs related to its Dalkon Shield birth-control device. <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> said its loss in the period compared to a profit of $ 26.2 million, or $ 1.08 a share, in the same period a year earlier. Revenue rose to $ 234.8 million from $ 210.8 million a year earlier. For all of 1987, <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> suffered a loss of $ 1.63 billion compared to a profit of $ 81.8 million, or $ 3.38 a share, in 1986. Revenue for the year rose to $ 855.8 million from $ 789.9 million. <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> was forced to set aside $ 1.75 billion last year to help cover the costs of claims concerning women who were injured by the Dalkon Shield, which has been discontinued. The accrual represents the difference between the $ 2.30 billion provided in the company's fifth amended reorganization plan and the $ 548 million which remained from the reserve for <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> claims established by the company in 1984. <PERSON> Robins </PERSON>' results were also hurt by the costs of its Chapter 11 reorganization in federal bankruptcy court. <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the president and chief executive, said consumer products in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, international operations and medical instruments were the principal contributors to the higher sales for the year.
