<HEAD>Flight Attendants Ask Airline To Agree To Arbitration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Teamsters union asked <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> on Monday to submit issues separating the company and its 6,500 flight attendants to binding arbitration. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> said it would not agree to arbitration but was willing to resume talks. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Genoese </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> airline division, said flight attendants were prepared to strike if the airline did not agree to arbitration in 72 hours. Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>'s administration backed the arbitration request, said state <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, who joined Genoese in a news conference at a Teamsters office in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The flight attendants, more than 2,000 of them based in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, have worked since a Feb. 26 strike deadline, but no talks have been held for the past week. Genoese cited economic and safety concerns as reasons for holding off on a strike this long. He referred to a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> report Friday on safety concerns at <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and said a strike would mean operating with less experienced replacement flight attendants. `` This would threaten both the comfort and safety of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> passengers,'' he said. Issues dividing the two sides include a two-tier wage system under which attendants hired after May 1984 must work five years to earn the same as those hired earlier. The airline proposes to extend the time to nine years. <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, `` without commenting on the merits of either side,'' said the <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> administration is concerned about the Detroit-based flight attendants' jobs and the potential economic impact of a strike. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> accounts for about half the air traffic in and out of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Metropolitan Airport, the largest of its three hubs. The airline operates about 248 flights a day at <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION>, about 227 at <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, where it is headquartered, and 201 at its <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, hub.
