<HEAD>Tentative Settlement Ends Threat of Strike at Key Stamping Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tentative settlement reached early Monday between the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, derailing the threat of a strike at a key Sterling Heights stamping plant. `` Obviously, the company is hopeful that the workers will ratify the agreement and that the threat of a strike will disappear,'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Northard </PERSON> said. Sterling Heights makes metal hoods and trunk lids for all domestically made <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> cars and most trucks and makes fuel tanks for all <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> cars except one. A strike there would soon have hurt all <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> production, and additional strikes at a few other key plants could have crippled <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> within days. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> had joined negotiations between <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 1264 on Friday, a day after <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced it would not sell its <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts subsidiary. The union would have been the first to receive <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>'s permission to strike over local issues such as health-and-safety grievances and violation of work rules <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> had promised to give immediate strike authorization to all locals with legitimate grievances. But after <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> decided to keep its 28,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, he began moving to resolve local disputes. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> and other negotiators bargained through the weekend and reached a tentative settlement on Local 1264's grievances at 5 a.m. Monday, the union said. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> was unavailable for comment Monday. The union said it was withholding details of the agreement until March 11, when the local's 3,600 active and 500 laid-off members will vote on the settlement. `` We saved a lot of jobs and got additional jobs,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, Local 1264 recording secretary and a member of the local's bargaining committee <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> agreed to add workers to clean up oil that leaks from the plants massive presses onto the shop floor and to clean and repair the machines as a matter of routine. Workers had complained that because the presses are run around the clock, they do n't receive adequate maintenance, particularly cleaning, and the machines and the floors around them are covered with oil and dirt. Local 1264 had accumulated nearly 140 unresolved grievances since last year. Other locals had been gathering grievances so they could be ready to strike if <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> had decided to sell <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION>.
