<HEAD>Top Brazilian Bankers Quit, Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Milliet </PERSON> resigned Monday and the government fired the president of the semi-official <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> do </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brasil </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Camilo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calazans </PERSON>, officials said. No immediate explanation was given for the dismissals. Milliet, the fourth <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> President under <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 3-year-old civilian regime, was in charge of negotiating the refinancing of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s huge $ 113 billion foreign debt Milliet was to be replaced by <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Araujo </PERSON> <PERSON> Camoes </PERSON>, an experienced banker with the Banco do <PERSON> Brasil </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Sao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paulo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banespa </ORGANIZATION> and the Sogeral bank. He is a member of the government's national monetary council. <PERSON> Calazans </PERSON>, an economist who used to head the government's coffee agency, reportedly disagreed with Finance Minister <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> about wage restrictions for federal employees. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> favored a wage freeze to reduce the federal deficit, but <PERSON> Calazans </PERSON> nevertheless granted a raise for <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> do Brasil employees. <PERSON> Calazans </PERSON> was to be replaced by <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Gusmao </PERSON> <PERSON> Berard </PERSON>, the secretary-general of the finance ministery and closely tied to da <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON>.
